Couldn't be better.

228
00:14:17,481 --> 00:14:20,191
That's good to hear.
I'm not gonna waste your time.

229
00:14:20,359 --> 00:14:22,485
You just tell me
what you're looking for.

230
00:14:22,653 --> 00:14:24,946
Fifty million dollars
in additional payroll.

231
00:14:25,114 --> 00:14:26,573
You should try Giambi.

232
00:14:26,740 --> 00:14:28,533
Ouch.
I'm sorry. Too soon, right?

233
00:14:28,701 --> 00:14:30,910
I want this to be
a friendly meeting.

234
00:14:31,078 --> 00:14:32,704
It's not all
on your shoulders.

235
00:14:32,872 --> 00:14:34,914
Where's Steve in this?
BILLY: Steve's great.

236
00:14:35,082 --> 00:14:37,125
He's supportive
in rebuilding this team.

237
00:14:37,293 --> 00:14:38,793
That's what we're gonna do.

238
00:14:38,961 --> 00:14:41,963
So, what are you looking for?
A left-handed reliever.

239
00:14:42,464 --> 00:14:44,966
I'm thinking Ricardo Rincon.

240
00:14:45,759 --> 00:14:47,302
That's not gonna happen.

241
00:14:48,846 --> 00:14:50,597
Not even a discussion?

242
00:14:50,764 --> 00:14:55,768
Billy, even if you could afford him,
respectfully, we love him.

243
00:14:55,936 --> 00:14:57,896
We're not about to let him go.

244
00:14:58,105 --> 00:15:00,064
You got this Venezuelan kid
coming up.

245
00:15:00,232 --> 00:15:02,567
We had him.
We moved him to Detroit.

246
00:15:02,735 --> 00:15:05,320
Huh.
What else you thinking?

247
00:15:06,488 --> 00:15:08,072
Outfielders.

248
00:15:08,240 --> 00:15:10,950
To replace Damon?
Yeah.

249
00:15:11,118 --> 00:15:14,954
In your price range? No disrespect.
Enough, Mark.

250
00:15:15,122 --> 00:15:17,457
Uh... Hollins?

251
00:15:18,167 --> 00:15:19,584
BILLY:
Uh-uh.

252
00:15:20,544 --> 00:15:23,129
Garcia?
No.

253
00:15:23,297 --> 00:15:25,006
Maybe Coste.

254
00:15:25,758 --> 00:15:27,216
Uh-uh.

255
00:15:27,968 --> 00:15:29,510
That's it.

256
00:15:30,846 --> 00:15:34,182
All right, tell me about Garcia.
To replace Johnny Damon?

257
00:15:34,850 --> 00:15:37,852
Mark, is he healthy?
Yeah, he's healthy-ish.

258
00:15:38,020 --> 00:15:40,480
He had that back thing.

259
00:15:40,648 --> 00:15:43,399
He'll be ready for spring ball.
BILLY: I'll tell you what.

260
00:15:43,567 --> 00:15:46,069
I can give you Guthrie
if you kick in some cash.

261
00:15:46,236 --> 00:15:47,320
Mark Guthrie?
Yeah.

262
00:15:47,488 --> 00:15:49,614
How much cash?
Two hundred K.

263
00:15:56,664 --> 00:16:05,797
[WHISPERS INDISTINCTLY]

264
00:16:05,965 --> 00:16:07,382
MARK:
Okay.

265
00:16:08,384 --> 00:16:12,220
So Garcia's gonna be a no.
You're kidding me, right?

266
00:16:13,138 --> 00:16:15,473
You're kidding me.
I'm not.

267
00:16:17,142 --> 00:16:20,395
Okay. Straight up,
Garcia for Guthrie, no kicker.

268
00:16:21,438 --> 00:16:24,065
No kicker?
BILLY: Straight up.

269
00:16:27,403 --> 00:16:32,031
I think it's gonna be
a hard no on Garcia,
but let's just keep going.

270
00:16:32,199 --> 00:16:35,410
What else you thinking?
What are we doing? Is this business?

271
00:16:35,577 --> 00:16:37,870
This is the way we do
business in Cleveland.

272
00:17:21,665 --> 00:17:23,082
Hey.

273
00:17:24,293 --> 00:17:26,794
Hello.
Who are you?

274
00:17:29,631 --> 00:17:31,632
I'm Peter Brand.

275
00:17:32,509 --> 00:17:34,260
What do you do?

276
00:17:35,637 --> 00:17:38,222
I'm special assistant
to Mark Shapiro.

277
00:17:38,390 --> 00:17:40,266
So, what do you do?

278
00:17:42,644 --> 00:17:46,105
Mostly player analysis
right now.

279
00:17:46,273 --> 00:17:49,984
Been on the job long?
First job in baseball?

280
00:17:51,445 --> 00:17:53,821
It's my first job anywhere.

281
00:17:53,989 --> 00:17:56,449
Wow, congrats.
Thank you.

282
00:17:56,617 --> 00:17:59,243
First job.
Whose nephew are you?

283
00:18:01,663 --> 00:18:03,498
Why does Mark listen to you?

284
00:18:06,126 --> 00:18:08,503
I don't think, uh...

285
00:18:08,670 --> 00:18:11,005
I don't think he does very often.

286
00:18:12,466 --> 00:18:14,342
He just did.

287
00:18:16,428 --> 00:18:17,970
Well, in that circumstance,

288
00:18:18,138 --> 00:18:21,682
I think he was more listening
to Bruce than myself.

289
00:18:22,101 --> 00:18:24,685
Mm-hm. Who are you?

290
00:18:27,397 --> 00:18:29,649
I'm Peter Brand.

291
00:18:32,653 --> 00:18:35,696
I don't give a rat's ass
what your name is.

292
00:18:36,406 --> 00:18:38,574
What happened
in there?

293
00:18:39,701 --> 00:18:41,994
What happened
in that room?

294
00:18:42,412 --> 00:18:45,123
I'm not quite sure what
you're asking me, Mr. Beane.

295
00:18:45,290 --> 00:18:47,708
What did you
tell Bruce?

296
00:18:48,877 --> 00:18:53,381
I just told Bruce I like Garcia.
You like Garcia. Why?

297
00:18:55,676 --> 00:18:57,385
Why?

298
00:19:02,432 --> 00:19:05,017
I don't know. Ahem.

299
00:19:21,577 --> 00:19:24,453
There is an epidemic failure
within the game

300
00:19:24,621 --> 00:19:27,248
to understand
what is really happening.

301
00:19:27,416 --> 00:19:31,878
And this leads people who run
Major League Baseball teams

302
00:19:32,045 --> 00:19:36,215
to misjudge their players
and mismanage their teams.

303
00:19:40,804 --> 00:19:42,763
I apologize.

304
00:19:43,724 --> 00:19:44,765
Go on.

305
00:19:48,020 --> 00:19:53,191
Okay. People who run ball clubs,
they think in terms of buying players.

306
00:19:53,775 --> 00:19:58,362
Your goal shouldn't be
to buy players. Your goal
should be to buy wins.

307
00:19:58,530 --> 00:20:01,908
And in order to buy wins,
you need to buy runs.

308
00:20:02,075 --> 00:20:04,118
You're trying
to replace Johnny Damon.

309
00:20:04,620 --> 00:20:06,245
The Red Sox see Johnny Damon

310
00:20:06,413 --> 00:20:10,082
and they see a star
who's worth $7.5 million a year.

311
00:20:10,250 --> 00:20:13,127
When I see Johnny Damon,

312
00:20:13,295 --> 00:20:15,630
what I see is...

313
00:20:17,049 --> 00:20:20,468
an imperfect understanding
of where runs come from.

314
00:20:21,178 --> 00:20:22,803
The guy's got a great glove.

315
00:20:22,971 --> 00:20:25,932
He's a decent leadoff hitter.
He can steal bases.

316
00:20:26,099 --> 00:20:28,476
But is he worth
the $7.5 million a year

317
00:20:28,644 --> 00:20:30,811
that the Boston Red Sox
are paying him?

318
00:20:30,979 --> 00:20:32,813
No. No.

319
00:20:33,398 --> 00:20:35,274
Baseball thinking is medieval.

320
00:20:35,442 --> 00:20:37,944
They are asking
all the wrong questions.

321
00:20:38,111 --> 00:20:42,281
And if I say it to anybody,
I'm ostracized. I'm a leper.

322
00:20:42,449 --> 00:20:47,411
So that's why I'm cagey
about this with you.

323
00:20:47,579 --> 00:20:48,621
That's why--

324
00:20:48,789 --> 00:20:52,708
I respect you, Mr. Beane,
and if you want full disclosure,

325
00:20:53,335 --> 00:20:57,755
I think it's a good thing
that you got Damon off
your payroll.

326
00:20:57,923 --> 00:21:02,468
I think it opens up all kinds
of interesting possibilities.

327
00:21:02,636 --> 00:21:05,721
Where you from, Pete?
Maryland.

328
00:21:05,889 --> 00:21:09,183
Where'd you go to school?
Yale. I went to Yale.

329
00:21:10,310 --> 00:21:13,187
What'd you study?
Economics.

330
00:21:13,855 --> 00:21:16,399
I studied economics.

331
00:21:17,943 --> 00:21:19,735
[ELEVATOR BELL DINGS]

332
00:21:19,945 --> 00:21:24,323
Yale, economics and baseball.

333
00:21:25,867 --> 00:21:28,119
You're funny, Pete.

334
00:21:47,723 --> 00:21:49,724
[♪♪♪]

335
00:21:51,018 --> 00:21:52,226
DAD:
Tell me, why Billy?

336
00:21:52,978 --> 00:21:55,354
What is it that makes him special?

337
00:21:55,522 --> 00:21:59,233
MAN:
Very rare do you come upon
a young man like Billy

338
00:21:59,401 --> 00:22:02,528
who can run, who can field,
who can throw, who can hit,

339
00:22:02,696 --> 00:22:04,280
and who can hit with power.

340
00:22:04,448 --> 00:22:07,491
Those five tools,
you don't see that very often.

341
00:22:08,160 --> 00:22:11,078
MARTINEZ:
Most of the youngsters
that we have an interest in

342
00:22:11,246 --> 00:22:12,705
have one or two tools,

343
00:22:12,873 --> 00:22:15,499
and we're hoping
to develop an extra one.

344
00:22:15,667 --> 00:22:17,585
Your son has five.

345
00:22:17,753 --> 00:22:21,797
We're looking at a guy
that's a potential superstar
for us in New York.

346
00:22:21,965 --> 00:22:23,841
The time is now
to get him started.

347
00:22:24,009 --> 00:22:26,844
We're prepared to make
a sizable financial commitment.

348
00:22:27,012 --> 00:22:29,430
The Mets are gonna
stand behind Billy

349
00:22:29,598 --> 00:22:32,933
because we expect him
to be our big-league center fielder.

350
00:22:33,101 --> 00:22:35,186
This check here
represents the offer

351
00:22:35,354 --> 00:22:38,731
that the New York Mets
would be making to Billy.

352
00:22:38,899 --> 00:22:44,028
You do know that he's been accepted
to Stanford on a full scholarship?

353
00:22:44,196 --> 00:22:45,363
JONGEWAARD:
I do.

354
00:22:45,530 --> 00:22:47,948
So he can do both?

355
00:22:48,116 --> 00:22:52,453
Unfortunately, he can't do Stanford
and professional baseball.

356
00:22:52,621 --> 00:22:56,540
He would have to pick one
or the other.

357
00:22:56,708 --> 00:22:59,210
If he wants to be center fielder
for the Mets,

358
00:22:59,378 --> 00:23:01,253
wants to be a baseball player,

359
00:23:01,421 --> 00:23:06,300
he really needs to accept this
as life's first occupation, first career.

360
00:23:06,468 --> 00:23:10,221
We're all told at some point we can
no longer play the children's game.

361
00:23:10,389 --> 00:23:12,890
We just don't know
when that's gonna be.

362
00:23:13,392 --> 00:23:17,478
Some of us are told at 18,
some of us are told at 40,
but we're all told.

363
00:23:18,105 --> 00:23:21,315
But this is a once-in-a-lifetime
opportunity.

364
00:23:21,483 --> 00:23:26,070
We want you badly,
and we think that this amount
of money expresses that desire.

365
00:23:26,238 --> 00:23:29,615
DAD: Billy, this is your decision,
and whatever that decision is,

366
00:23:29,783 --> 00:23:32,284
you know it's fine
with your mother and I.

367
00:23:37,165 --> 00:23:38,499
[CELL PHONE RINGING]

368
00:23:43,171 --> 00:23:45,423
PETER: Hello?
Hey, it's Billy Beane.

369
00:23:46,216 --> 00:23:50,010
Hey, what time is it?
I don't know.

370
00:23:50,971 --> 00:23:55,141
Listen, would you have
drafted me in the first round?

371
00:23:55,308 --> 00:23:56,725
What?

372
00:23:56,893 --> 00:24:00,438
After I left, you looked me up
on your computer.

373
00:24:00,605 --> 00:24:02,940
Would you have drafted me
in the first round?

374
00:24:03,108 --> 00:24:06,026
I did, yeah.
You were a good player.

375
00:24:06,194 --> 00:24:08,446
Cut the crap, man.

376
00:24:08,613 --> 00:24:11,532
Would you have drafted me
in the first round?

377
00:24:12,200 --> 00:24:16,370
I'd have taken you
in the ninth round.
No signing bonus.

378
00:24:17,205 --> 00:24:21,709
I imagine you would've passed
and taken that scholarship.

379
00:24:22,377 --> 00:24:24,295
Yeah.

380
00:24:27,883 --> 00:24:30,384
Pack your bags, Pete.

381
00:24:30,802 --> 00:24:33,846
I just bought you
from the Cleveland Indians.

382
00:24:40,896 --> 00:24:42,229
[SIGHS]

383
00:24:44,232 --> 00:24:46,400
[MEN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

384
00:24:47,569 --> 00:24:51,071
MAN 1: Is it attached to that clamp?
MAN 2: Yeah, let me unhook it.

385
00:24:59,372 --> 00:25:00,748
MAN 3:
Slide it up right there.

386
00:25:00,916 --> 00:25:02,166
To the left.
MAN 4: I did.

387
00:25:02,334 --> 00:25:04,418
MAN 5: Yeah, yeah.
MAN 6: Hang on, it's wet.

388
00:25:04,586 --> 00:25:06,170
Come on.

389
00:25:10,842 --> 00:25:12,843
[♪♪♪]

390
00:25:27,943 --> 00:25:29,568
Morning, Suzanne. Coffee on?
Yes.

391
00:25:29,736 --> 00:25:30,778
Great.

392
00:25:30,946 --> 00:25:31,987
[PHONE RINGS]

393
00:25:32,155 --> 00:25:33,781
SUZANNE: Billy Beane's office.
PETER: Hey.

394
00:25:33,949 --> 00:25:34,949
Peter Brand.
Billy.

395
00:25:35,116 --> 00:25:37,618
How are--? Hi, how you doing?
Nice to see you.

396
00:25:37,786 --> 00:25:40,371
Good to have you here.
Boy, you move in fast.

397
00:25:40,539 --> 00:25:42,540
Yeah, yeah.
I got here early this morning.

398
00:25:42,707 --> 00:25:44,833
Wow. Huh.

399
00:25:45,001 --> 00:25:47,086
All moved in.
Yeah.

400
00:25:47,796 --> 00:25:49,380
PETER:
Yeah.

401
00:25:49,548 --> 00:25:51,549
Hey, Billy,

402
00:25:51,716 --> 00:25:54,635
I wanted you to see
these player evaluations

403
00:25:54,803 --> 00:25:56,971
that you asked me to do.

404
00:25:57,931 --> 00:25:59,557
I asked you to do three.

405
00:26:00,475 --> 00:26:01,809
Yeah.

406
00:26:01,977 --> 00:26:04,562
To evaluate three players.
Yeah.

407
00:26:04,729 --> 00:26:06,689
How many did you do?

408
00:26:06,856 --> 00:26:08,816
Forty-seven.

409
00:26:09,734 --> 00:26:11,277
Okay.

410
00:26:12,153 --> 00:26:15,906
Actually, 51.
I don't know why I lied just then.

411
00:26:24,916 --> 00:26:27,334
Why don't you walk me
through the board?

412
00:26:28,795 --> 00:26:30,379
Thank you.

413
00:26:35,802 --> 00:26:37,803
[♪♪♪]

414
00:26:56,656 --> 00:26:58,699
PETER:
Using this equation
in the upper left,

415
00:26:58,867 --> 00:27:01,994
I'm projecting that we need
to win at least 99 games

416
00:27:02,162 --> 00:27:04,330
in order to make it
to the postseason.

417
00:27:04,497 --> 00:27:08,626
We need to score at least 814 runs
in order to win those games

418
00:27:08,793 --> 00:27:11,879
and allow no more
than 645 runs.

419
00:27:17,010 --> 00:27:18,302
BILLY:
What's this?

420
00:27:18,470 --> 00:27:22,056
PETER:
This is a code that I've written
for our year-to-year projections.

421
00:27:22,223 --> 00:27:25,893
This is building in the intelligence
that we have to project players.

422
00:27:26,061 --> 00:27:27,061
BILLY:
Okay.

423
00:27:27,228 --> 00:27:29,897
PETER:
It's about getting things down
to one number.

424
00:27:30,357 --> 00:27:32,900
Using the stats
the way we read them,

425
00:27:33,068 --> 00:27:36,236
we'll find value in players
that nobody else can see.

426
00:27:39,741 --> 00:27:41,075
People are overlooked

427
00:27:41,242 --> 00:27:45,037
for a variety of biased reasons
and perceived flaws.

428
00:27:45,205 --> 00:27:48,499
Age, appearance, personality.

429
00:27:48,667 --> 00:27:53,420
Bill James and mathematics
cut straight through that.

430
00:27:55,006 --> 00:27:58,300
Billy, of the 20,000 notable players
for us to consider,

431
00:27:58,468 --> 00:28:01,011
I believe that there is
a championship team

432
00:28:01,179 --> 00:28:04,348
of 25 people that we can afford,

433
00:28:04,516 --> 00:28:07,685
because everyone else
in baseball undervalues them.

434
00:28:07,852 --> 00:28:11,105
Like an island of misfit toys.

435
00:28:15,568 --> 00:28:18,779
Billy, this is Chad Bradford.
He's a relief pitcher.

436
00:28:18,947 --> 00:28:23,242
He is one of the most undervalued
players in baseball.

437
00:28:23,410 --> 00:28:26,370
His defect is that he throws funny.

438
00:28:27,205 --> 00:28:31,291
Nobody in the big leagues cares
about him because he looks funny.

439
00:28:31,459 --> 00:28:34,545
This guy could be not just
the best pitcher in our pen,

440
00:28:34,713 --> 00:28:38,132
but one of the most effective
relief pitchers in all baseball.

441
00:28:38,299 --> 00:28:41,051
This guy should cost
$3 million a year.

442
00:28:41,219 --> 00:28:44,096
We can get him for 237,000.

443
00:29:07,996 --> 00:29:09,455
PETER:
Billy.

444
00:29:10,957 --> 00:29:13,375
That it?
Yeah.

445
00:29:36,316 --> 00:29:38,317
[MEN CHATTERING NEARBY]

446
00:29:39,194 --> 00:29:40,694
[FOOTSTEPS]

447
00:29:43,531 --> 00:29:44,865
Hey, Art.

448
00:29:45,033 --> 00:29:47,242
Can I talk to you
before you get started?

449
00:29:47,410 --> 00:29:49,870
I'm a bit busy right now.
I know.

450
00:29:51,748 --> 00:29:53,332
I know.
BILLY: Okay.

451
00:29:53,500 --> 00:29:55,167
Morning, everyone.
Art.

452
00:29:55,335 --> 00:29:58,587
Peter Brand. Nice to meet you.
Where the hell's Pete?

453
00:29:58,755 --> 00:29:59,838
That's Pete.

454
00:30:00,715 --> 00:30:03,217
Grab a seat.
I'll be right back.

455
00:30:04,344 --> 00:30:06,386
POLONI: All right,
where did you say he's at?

456
00:30:06,554 --> 00:30:07,638
KEOUGH:
Okay. He's on--

457
00:30:08,348 --> 00:30:11,016
Who's the kid?
A friend of mine.

458
00:30:12,769 --> 00:30:15,729
I can't manage this team
under a one-year contract.

459
00:30:15,897 --> 00:30:17,689
Well, sure you can.

460
00:30:19,400 --> 00:30:21,527
No, I can't.

461
00:30:21,694 --> 00:30:24,238
Okay. I gotta put a team
on the field.

462
00:30:24,405 --> 00:30:27,908
After that, I'll take a good
long look at your contract.

463
00:30:28,076 --> 00:30:31,370
Deal with the manager's contract,
then put a team on the field.

464
00:30:31,538 --> 00:30:35,916
At this moment, if a grounder's hit
to first, nobody's there to stop it.

465
00:30:36,751 --> 00:30:41,088
It's not easy doing what
I do under the cloud of
a one-year contract.

466
00:30:41,256 --> 00:30:42,673
Okay, I understand that.

467
00:30:42,841 --> 00:30:44,800
I've been there.
I know you have.

468
00:30:44,968 --> 00:30:49,429
A one-year contract means
the same thing to a manager
as to a player.

469
00:30:49,597 --> 00:30:51,765
There's not a lot of faith there.

470
00:30:51,933 --> 00:30:54,726
Which is strange
after a 102-win season.

471
00:30:55,770 --> 00:30:57,729
I see.

472
00:30:57,897 --> 00:31:02,234
If you lose the last game
of the season, nobody gives a shit.

473
00:31:04,279 --> 00:31:08,115
So it's on me now?
No, Art, it's on me.

474
00:31:08,283 --> 00:31:11,618
And the kid
is the new assistant GM.

475
00:31:11,786 --> 00:31:13,787
Okay.
BILLY: Okay, fellas.

476
00:31:13,955 --> 00:31:15,622
GRADY:
Hey, Billy.

477
00:31:25,967 --> 00:31:28,719
You can't deny his
offensive output. He can play.

478
00:31:28,887 --> 00:31:31,889
And we need people
that can play.

479
00:31:38,104 --> 00:31:40,480
Who do you wanna
talk about first?

480
00:31:57,248 --> 00:31:59,249
None of them.

481
00:32:00,001 --> 00:32:02,961
Billy, we got 38 home runs,
120 RBIs to make up for.

482
00:32:03,129 --> 00:32:05,505
Guys, you're still trying
to replace Giambi.

483
00:32:05,673 --> 00:32:09,176
I told you we can't do it,
and we can't do it.

484
00:32:09,719 --> 00:32:13,931
Now, what we might be able
to do is re-create him.

485
00:32:14,098 --> 00:32:17,100
Re-create him in the aggregate.
GRADY: The what?

486
00:32:17,268 --> 00:32:20,020
Giambi's on-base percentage
was .477.

487
00:32:20,188 --> 00:32:24,650
Damon's on-base, .324.
And Olmedo's was .291.

488
00:32:24,817 --> 00:32:27,027
Add that up and you get...

489
00:32:29,697 --> 00:32:30,989
Do you want me to speak?

490
00:32:32,033 --> 00:32:33,867
When I point at you, yeah.

491
00:32:34,035 --> 00:32:36,036
1 .092.
BILLY: Divided by three.

492
00:32:36,204 --> 00:32:37,245
[SNAPS FINGERS]

493
00:32:37,413 --> 00:32:39,915
.364.
That's what we're looking for.

494
00:32:40,083 --> 00:32:44,211
Three ballplayers--
Three ballplayers
whose average OBP is...

495
00:32:44,379 --> 00:32:45,712
.364.

496
00:32:45,880 --> 00:32:48,757
Wait, that doesn't come out right.
BILLY: It's right, Artie.

497
00:32:49,425 --> 00:32:51,218
GRADY: Billy.
You gotta carry the one.

498
00:32:51,386 --> 00:32:53,762
Billy.
Scratch this out.

499
00:32:53,930 --> 00:32:55,013
Yeah?

500
00:32:55,181 --> 00:32:56,765
GRADY:
Who's that?

501
00:32:56,933 --> 00:32:58,558
That's Pete.

502
00:32:59,477 --> 00:33:02,062
GRADY:
Does Pete really need to be here?

503
00:33:02,230 --> 00:33:03,230
Yes, he does.

504
00:33:04,857 --> 00:33:07,234
Okay, here's who we want.

505
00:33:07,402 --> 00:33:10,654
Number one:
Jason's little brother, Jeremy.

506
00:33:10,822 --> 00:33:13,699
KEOUGH: Oh, God.
Billy, that's trouble.

507
00:33:13,866 --> 00:33:18,745
Billy, look, if I-- Yeah.
Billy, if I may, he's had
his problems off the field,

508
00:33:18,913 --> 00:33:21,248
and we know what he can't do
on the field.

509
00:33:21,416 --> 00:33:23,333
PITTARO:
He's getting thick around the waist.

510
00:33:23,501 --> 00:33:26,169
There's reports about him
on weed, in strip clubs.

511
00:33:26,337 --> 00:33:29,006
His on-base percentage
is all we're looking at now.

512
00:33:29,173 --> 00:33:34,594
And Jeremy gets on base
an awful lot for a guy
who only costs 285,000.

513
00:33:34,762 --> 00:33:37,764
PITTARO: Jeez, Billy--
BILLY: Number two:

514
00:33:39,392 --> 00:33:41,268
David Justice.
Oh, no.

515
00:33:41,436 --> 00:33:43,311
ARTIE: His legs are gone.
Not a good idea.

516
00:33:43,479 --> 00:33:45,105
PITTARO: Old Man Justice?
BILLY: Why is that?

517
00:33:45,273 --> 00:33:50,402
Steinbrenner's so pissed at
his decline, he's willing to eat
his contract to get rid of him.

518
00:33:50,570 --> 00:33:53,280
Exactly.
Ten years ago, Justice, big name.

519
00:33:53,448 --> 00:33:54,489
Been in big games.

520
00:33:54,657 --> 00:33:57,909
He's gonna really help
our season tickets
early in the year,

521
00:33:58,077 --> 00:34:02,706
but in the dog days in July,
August, we're lucky if he's
gonna hit his weight.

522
00:34:02,874 --> 00:34:06,543
Billy, his legs are gone,
and he's a defensive liability.

523
00:34:06,711 --> 00:34:08,879
I question whether
the bat speed's there.

524
00:34:09,047 --> 00:34:10,505
His legs are gone.
BILLY: Grady.

525
00:34:10,673 --> 00:34:14,593
We'll be lucky to get 60 games
out of him. Why do you like him?

526
00:34:15,636 --> 00:34:16,970
Because he gets on base.

527
00:34:18,806 --> 00:34:20,557
HOPKINS: What is this?
BARRY: What are we doing?

528
00:34:20,725 --> 00:34:22,809
BILLY:
Okay, number three:

529
00:34:22,977 --> 00:34:24,978
[MARKER SQUEAKING]

530
00:34:28,649 --> 00:34:30,567
Scott Hatteberg.
MAN 1: Who?

531
00:34:30,735 --> 00:34:31,818
MAN 2: Hatteberg?
Exactly.

532
00:34:31,986 --> 00:34:33,820
He sounds like an Oakland A
already.

533
00:34:33,988 --> 00:34:37,991
Yes, he's had a little problem with--
Little problem? He can't throw.

534
00:34:38,159 --> 00:34:41,828
He's a career .260 hitter.
The best part of his career is over.

535
00:34:41,996 --> 00:34:44,790
It's just getting started.
Boston wants to cut him.

536
00:34:44,957 --> 00:34:47,501
No one wants to pick him up.
Good. He's cheap.

537
00:34:47,668 --> 00:34:50,337
GRADY:
Let me get this straight.
You're gonna get a guy

538
00:34:50,505 --> 00:34:53,840
that's been released by
half the organizations
in baseball

539
00:34:54,008 --> 00:34:58,178
because he's got
nonrepairable nerve damage
in his elbow and can't throw.

540
00:34:58,346 --> 00:35:01,681
He can't throw
and he can't field.
But what can he do?

541
00:35:01,849 --> 00:35:02,891
MAN 3:
Oh, boy.

542
00:35:03,059 --> 00:35:05,477
Check your reports
or I'm gonna point at Pete.

543
00:35:05,645 --> 00:35:08,146
ALL: He gets on base.
He can get on base.

544
00:35:08,314 --> 00:35:10,899
So he walks a lot.
He gets on base a lot, Rocco.

545
00:35:11,067 --> 00:35:13,693
Do I care
if it's a walk or a hit?

546
00:35:13,861 --> 00:35:15,237
Pete?

547
00:35:15,404 --> 00:35:17,656
You do not.
BILLY: I do not.

548
00:35:17,824 --> 00:35:20,867
BARRY: I got 37 free agents
that are better than those three guys.

549
00:35:21,035 --> 00:35:23,286
Wait a minute,
let me get this straight.

550
00:35:23,454 --> 00:35:26,123
So you're not gonna bring in one

551
00:35:26,290 --> 00:35:29,626
but three defective players
to replace Giambi?

552
00:35:30,336 --> 00:35:32,796
You're not buying into
this Bill James bullshit?

553
00:35:32,964 --> 00:35:34,965
BILLY: This is the new
direction of the A's.

554
00:35:35,133 --> 00:35:38,051
We are card counters
at the blackjack table

555
00:35:38,219 --> 00:35:40,929
and we're gonna turn the odds
on the casino.

556
00:35:42,265 --> 00:35:44,015
I don't see it.
POTE: Seriously, guys.

557
00:35:44,183 --> 00:35:46,893
I think we have to remember
this is the man.

558
00:35:47,061 --> 00:35:52,482
He answers to no one
except ownership and God.

559
00:35:52,650 --> 00:35:55,527
And he doesn't
have to answer to us.

560
00:35:55,695 --> 00:35:58,113
We make suggestions,
he makes decisions.

561
00:35:58,281 --> 00:36:01,700
That's all fine and well,
but we've been working
our asses off

562
00:36:01,868 --> 00:36:05,704
for weeks to make this club better,
and you're shitting all over it.

563
00:36:05,872 --> 00:36:08,373
This is not a discussion.

564
00:36:10,710 --> 00:36:12,085
BARRY:
What are we discussing?

565
00:36:12,253 --> 00:36:14,087
Barry, not a discussion.

566
00:36:19,093 --> 00:36:21,970
WASHINGTON:
Billy, man, um,

567
00:36:22,597 --> 00:36:24,681
there's one thing
you're forgetting.

568
00:36:25,266 --> 00:36:30,020
None of those three guys
knows how to play first base.

569
00:36:30,188 --> 00:36:32,522
Well, you're gonna have
to teach one of them.

570
00:36:32,690 --> 00:36:34,107
WASHINGTON:
Teach?

571
00:36:35,234 --> 00:36:36,943
Which one?

572
00:36:43,784 --> 00:36:45,619
[♪♪♪]

573
00:36:48,456 --> 00:36:52,584
WOMAN [ON TV]: This is really
the kickoff to the holiday season
here in downtown Seattle.

574
00:36:52,752 --> 00:36:57,130
It took weeks of planning
to lead up to the big event,
but it was well worth it.

575
00:36:57,298 --> 00:37:00,759
The weather was ideal.
People are still having a great time.

576
00:37:00,927 --> 00:37:02,802
Thousands of people
were out earlier.

577
00:37:02,970 --> 00:37:04,638
MAN:
We have a nice recap for you

578
00:37:04,805 --> 00:37:08,308
of all the great events taking place
downtown in Seattle--

579
00:37:08,476 --> 00:37:10,477
[PHONE RINGING]

580
00:37:12,355 --> 00:37:13,980
Hello?
BILLY: Scott?

581
00:37:14,148 --> 00:37:15,148
Yes.

582
00:37:15,316 --> 00:37:18,318
It's Billy Beane of the Oakland A's.
Yes.

583
00:37:18,486 --> 00:37:21,363
Can we talk?
Uh, yeah.

584
00:37:21,530 --> 00:37:23,490
Do you wanna let us in?

585
00:37:24,492 --> 00:37:27,035
Pardon me?
We're out front.

586
00:37:28,496 --> 00:37:30,664
What?
On the curb.

587
00:37:30,831 --> 00:37:32,624
Uh, yeah, yeah.

588
00:37:34,543 --> 00:37:35,627
Honey?

589
00:37:40,007 --> 00:37:42,008
Oh, thank you.
Thank you, ma'am.

590
00:37:42,176 --> 00:37:43,843
Very kind.

591
00:37:47,348 --> 00:37:49,182
How's the elbow, Scott?

592
00:37:49,350 --> 00:37:53,395
You know, it's good.
It's really good. It's great. Uh...

593
00:37:59,235 --> 00:38:01,361
I can't throw the ball at all.
BILLY: Yeah.

594
00:38:01,529 --> 00:38:04,239
You've thrown your last ball
from behind home plate.

595
00:38:04,407 --> 00:38:06,616
That's what I'd say.
Well...

596
00:38:07,326 --> 00:38:10,620
Good news is,
we want you at first.

597
00:38:17,920 --> 00:38:21,464
We want you to play
first base for the Oakland A's.

598
00:38:22,633 --> 00:38:24,843
Okay, well,

599
00:38:25,011 --> 00:38:26,761
I've only ever played catcher.

600
00:38:26,929 --> 00:38:29,389
Scott, you're not
a catcher anymore.

601
00:38:30,474 --> 00:38:33,893
If you were, our call wouldn't
have been the only one you got.

602
00:38:34,812 --> 00:38:38,982
Yeah. Hey, listen, no, I appreciate it.
You're welcome.

603
00:38:39,150 --> 00:38:43,903
But the thing is, is...
You don't know how to play first base.

604
00:38:44,488 --> 00:38:45,572
Scott.
That's right.

605
00:38:46,073 --> 00:38:47,657
It's not that hard, Scott.

606
00:38:47,825 --> 00:38:50,035
Tell him, Wash.
It's incredibly hard.

607
00:38:50,202 --> 00:38:53,371
Hey, anything worth doing is.
And we're gonna teach you.

608
00:38:53,539 --> 00:38:55,874
Wait a minute here.
I mean, but what about--?

609
00:38:56,042 --> 00:38:58,168
Jason's gone, Scott.

610
00:38:58,627 --> 00:39:01,171
You want me to take
Giambi's spot at first base?

611
00:39:01,339 --> 00:39:02,589
Yeah.
What about the fans?

612
00:39:02,757 --> 00:39:06,259
Maybe I can teach one of them.
The fans don't-- Good one.

613
00:39:06,427 --> 00:39:07,802
Fans don't run
my ball club.

614
00:39:07,970 --> 00:39:10,180
SCOTT:
Honey, what are you doing awake?

615
00:39:10,931 --> 00:39:12,932
Sweetheart, can you...?

616
00:39:14,101 --> 00:39:15,894
That's my daughter.

617
00:39:17,271 --> 00:39:19,230
You got kids?

618
00:39:20,107 --> 00:39:22,025
Uh, yeah, a daughter.

619
00:39:22,193 --> 00:39:26,613
Scott, this is a contract to play ball
for the Oakland A's.

620
00:39:26,781 --> 00:39:28,865
A copy's been sent over
to your agent.

621
00:39:29,033 --> 00:39:31,910
Discuss with your wife,
let us know.

622
00:39:32,953 --> 00:39:34,162
Thank you.

623
00:39:34,330 --> 00:39:35,622
Bye-bye.
Bye.

624
00:39:35,790 --> 00:39:37,791
Oh, and, Scott.
SCOTT: Yeah?

625
00:39:37,958 --> 00:39:40,001
Don't tell anyone
about the first-base thing.

626
00:39:40,169 --> 00:39:41,461
Yes, sir.
Okay.

627
00:39:41,629 --> 00:39:44,130
Happy holidays.
All right.

628
00:39:44,298 --> 00:39:46,299
[♪♪♪]

629
00:39:58,813 --> 00:40:00,146
[DOORBELL RINGS]

630
00:40:09,740 --> 00:40:10,990
Hey, Sharon.
Hi, Billy.

631
00:40:11,158 --> 00:40:14,411
Is she ready?
She's out with friends.

632
00:40:15,496 --> 00:40:17,622
But she'll be back. Come in.

633
00:40:18,332 --> 00:40:20,667
Okay.
MAN: Yeah, she's right here. Hold on.

634
00:40:20,835 --> 00:40:22,168
Here you go.

635
00:40:24,296 --> 00:40:27,924
Here, wanna have a seat?
Yeah.

636
00:40:36,559 --> 00:40:38,852
You good, Billy?
Yeah. How are you, Alan?

637
00:40:39,019 --> 00:40:42,397
Good. Really good.
Things are peaceful
around here.

638
00:40:44,442 --> 00:40:46,526
It's good to see you.

639
00:40:46,694 --> 00:40:48,653
Thanks, Alan.

640
00:40:48,821 --> 00:40:50,947
I haven't got to see you
since play-offs.

641
00:40:51,115 --> 00:40:53,616
I wanted to say that New York
was heartbreaking.

642
00:40:54,243 --> 00:40:55,660
I'm sure for you too.

643
00:40:55,828 --> 00:40:59,789
Not many teams make it that far,
and to watch you go that far was--

644
00:40:59,957 --> 00:41:05,462
It was really an accomplishment.
Well, that's nice.

645
00:41:06,297 --> 00:41:08,548
How is the team shaping up?

646
00:41:08,716 --> 00:41:12,469
Team's good. Rebuilding.
SHARON: Good.

647
00:41:12,636 --> 00:41:15,722
I read you lost
Giambonni and Damon.

648
00:41:15,890 --> 00:41:16,890
Giambi.
Giambi.

649
00:41:17,057 --> 00:41:19,726
Yeah.
Damon, Isringhausen.

650
00:41:19,894 --> 00:41:23,897
They're really--? They're gone?
Gone. Yesterday's news.

651
00:41:24,064 --> 00:41:27,442
ALAN: That's terrible.
No, but that is a tough situation.

652
00:41:27,610 --> 00:41:29,235
That's...

653
00:41:29,403 --> 00:41:32,780
You're gonna be fine, though.
You always figure something out.

654
00:41:36,619 --> 00:41:39,913
Where is she?
Where was she?
Down the street or...?

655
00:41:40,080 --> 00:41:44,083
Oh, sorry, yeah. I just
talked to her on her cell.
She's coming up the hill.

656
00:41:44,251 --> 00:41:45,543
Okay.

657
00:41:45,711 --> 00:41:47,921
She's got a cell phone?

658
00:41:48,422 --> 00:41:51,007
SHARON: Yeah.
A 12-year-old?

659
00:41:51,175 --> 00:41:52,675
Yeah.

660
00:41:53,260 --> 00:41:54,677
Huh.

661
00:41:55,596 --> 00:41:56,763
For emergencies.

662
00:41:58,766 --> 00:42:00,934
Big parenting decision.

663
00:42:01,435 --> 00:42:05,563
But it's something that,
you know, we, you know,
all should discuss,

664
00:42:05,731 --> 00:42:09,192
because if you have
any objections, of course...

665
00:42:09,360 --> 00:42:11,819
Her mother and I
will discuss it.

666
00:42:12,696 --> 00:42:14,405
But thank you.

667
00:42:17,409 --> 00:42:19,702
Any of these?
Um...

668
00:42:19,870 --> 00:42:21,371
I don't know.

669
00:42:21,539 --> 00:42:23,581
Do you--?
This one's cool.

670
00:42:23,749 --> 00:42:25,291
BILLY:
Is that good or bad?

671
00:42:25,459 --> 00:42:27,377
Butterflies.
CASEY: They're okay.

672
00:42:27,545 --> 00:42:30,505
Look, that one's pretty.
I like the red.

673
00:42:30,673 --> 00:42:32,298
Should we try?

674
00:42:33,008 --> 00:42:34,300
No?

675
00:42:34,468 --> 00:42:36,094
Oh, I like this one.
Yeah?

676
00:42:36,262 --> 00:42:37,637
Dad, look at this one.

677
00:42:37,805 --> 00:42:40,098
Look how it's red.
It's beautiful.

678
00:42:40,266 --> 00:42:42,642
This one's pretty.
Let's try it out.

679
00:42:42,810 --> 00:42:45,186
Just right here?
Why don't we go over there?

680
00:42:45,354 --> 00:42:46,896
Can we go over there?

681
00:42:48,023 --> 00:42:50,858
[CASEY HUMMING "THE SHOW"]

682
00:43:05,457 --> 00:43:09,502
Oh, honey, you need to sing.
That's so good.

683
00:43:10,254 --> 00:43:12,338
That's beautiful.

684
00:43:13,882 --> 00:43:14,924
Sometimes I sing.

685
00:43:15,092 --> 00:43:20,763
It's fun to sing with
your song, but I don't
want people to listen to me.

686
00:43:20,931 --> 00:43:24,809
Well, honey, I think people
would love to listen to you.
That's beautiful.

687
00:43:25,769 --> 00:43:28,896
Would you sing a little
for your dad?

688
00:43:29,064 --> 00:43:31,190
Right here
in the middle of the store?

689
00:43:34,028 --> 00:43:36,446
Little bit.
Little bit.

690
00:43:38,198 --> 00:43:39,907
You ready?
I'm ready.

691
00:43:40,075 --> 00:43:41,326
Okay.

692
00:43:41,493 --> 00:43:44,329
♪ I'm just a little bit
Caught in the middle ♪

693
00:43:44,496 --> 00:43:47,206
♪ Life is a maze
And love is a riddle ♪

694
00:43:47,374 --> 00:43:51,711
♪ I don't know where to go
Can't do it alone, I've tried ♪

695
00:43:51,879 --> 00:43:53,546
♪ And I don't know why ♪

696
00:43:53,714 --> 00:43:56,299
♪ I'm just a little girl
Lost in the moment ♪

697
00:43:56,467 --> 00:43:59,552
♪ I'm so scared
But I don't show it ♪

698
00:43:59,720 --> 00:44:02,889
♪ I can't figure it out
It's bringing me down ♪

699
00:44:03,057 --> 00:44:07,477
♪ I know I've got to let it go ♪

700
00:44:07,645 --> 00:44:10,563
♪ And just enjoy the show ♪♪

701
00:44:15,778 --> 00:44:19,030
ANNOUNCER 1:
Billy Beane was taken in the
first round of the amateur draft.

702
00:44:19,198 --> 00:44:21,449
ANNOUNCER 2:
I think this is a steal,
to get Billy Beane.

703
00:44:21,617 --> 00:44:23,159
He's young, he's talented.

704
00:44:23,327 --> 00:44:27,664
A true five-tool player with speed.
This guy is a can't-miss prospect.

705
00:44:27,831 --> 00:44:30,083
This is a great sign
for the New York Mets.

706
00:44:30,250 --> 00:44:33,711
ANNOUNCER 1:
And it could be the turnaround
that they've been looking for.

707
00:44:34,129 --> 00:44:35,588
UMPIRE:
Ball one.

708
00:44:35,756 --> 00:44:38,299
ANNOUNCER 1:
I'll take Billy Beane
over Strawberry.

