942
00:58:53,905 --> 00:58:56,698
I'm reinvigorated
by my love of the game.

943
00:59:02,121 --> 00:59:04,164
[♪♪♪]

944
00:59:20,056 --> 00:59:23,475
HOST [ON RADIO]:
We got Grady Fuson, former head
of scouting with the Athletics.

945
00:59:23,643 --> 00:59:26,436
And, Grady, can you interpret for us
what's going on?

946
00:59:26,604 --> 00:59:28,772
GRADY: They call it Moneyball.
HOST: Moneyball?

947
00:59:28,940 --> 00:59:33,485
GRADY:
Yes, and it was a nice theory,
and now it's just not working out.

948
00:59:33,653 --> 00:59:37,656
COMMENTATOR:
Billy Beane has built this team
on the ideas of a guy, Bill James,

949
00:59:37,824 --> 00:59:42,494
who wrote an interesting book
on baseball statistics.

950
00:59:42,662 --> 00:59:46,665
The problem is that Bill James
never played, never managed.

951
00:59:46,833 --> 00:59:51,420
He was in fact a security guard
at a pork-and-beans company.

952
00:59:51,588 --> 00:59:54,256
HOST:
Do you see this as a decimation
of the organization?

953
00:59:54,424 --> 00:59:56,091
GRADY:
He bought a ticket on the Titanic.

954
00:59:56,259 --> 00:59:57,301
HOST:
Oh, boy.

955
00:59:57,468 --> 00:59:59,511
COMMENTATOR:
He's tried to come up
with a new approach.

956
00:59:59,679 --> 01:00:02,764
My hat's off to him. It won't work.

957
01:00:03,516 --> 01:00:06,560
ANNOUNCER [ON RADIO]:
One-two pitch. Tejada strikes out.

958
01:00:06,728 --> 01:00:07,894
And that is the game.

959
01:00:08,062 --> 01:00:11,148
The Seattle Mariners
win both games on this series, Ray.

960
01:00:11,316 --> 01:00:14,860
They've won 10 in a row.
Seattle is 13 and 3.

961
01:00:17,530 --> 01:00:19,865
I can't watch this shit.

962
01:00:20,992 --> 01:00:22,534
Go on the road with the team.

963
01:00:22,702 --> 01:00:24,911
You don't go on the road
with the team.

964
01:00:25,079 --> 01:00:28,707
That's why I want you to do it.
Why don't you?

965
01:00:30,209 --> 01:00:33,045
I can't develop personal
relationships with these guys.

966
01:00:33,212 --> 01:00:35,756
I gotta be able to trade them,
send them down,

967
01:00:35,923 --> 01:00:37,758
sometimes cut them.

968
01:00:39,927 --> 01:00:42,888
Which is something
you should learn to do,
by the way.

969
01:00:45,558 --> 01:00:48,644
I would never have to
cut a player, unless you...

970
01:00:49,395 --> 01:00:52,397
Oh, come on.
"Come on" what?

971
01:00:52,565 --> 01:00:55,067
Let's practice.
No.

972
01:00:55,234 --> 01:00:58,111
Yeah. I'm a player.
You gotta cut me from the roster.

973
01:00:58,279 --> 01:00:59,321
No.
Go.

974
01:00:59,489 --> 01:01:00,947
What do you mean, no?
No.

975
01:01:01,115 --> 01:01:02,741
Do it.
This is stupid.

976
01:01:03,201 --> 01:01:05,327
Part of the job, man.

977
01:01:09,749 --> 01:01:11,249
Fine.

978
01:01:12,585 --> 01:01:16,046
Billy, please have a seat.
I need to talk to you for a minute.

979
01:01:16,214 --> 01:01:17,756
Go on.

980
01:01:19,092 --> 01:01:21,176
You've been a huge part
of this team.

981
01:01:21,344 --> 01:01:24,137
But sometimes you have to
make decisions for the team.

982
01:01:24,305 --> 01:01:25,931
I'm sure you can understand.

983
01:01:26,099 --> 01:01:29,101
You're cutting me?
I'm really sorry.

984
01:01:29,936 --> 01:01:31,436
I just bought a house here.

985
01:01:31,604 --> 01:01:33,271
Well...
In Oakland.

986
01:01:37,026 --> 01:01:38,610
Well, uh... Well...

987
01:01:38,778 --> 01:01:42,030
"Well... Well..."?
That's all you got to say?

988
01:01:42,198 --> 01:01:44,574
My kid just started
a new school.

989
01:01:44,742 --> 01:01:48,078
They made friends.
That's, uh...

990
01:01:48,621 --> 01:01:51,456
You shouldn't pull them out
in the middle of the year.

991
01:01:51,624 --> 01:01:54,459
You should wait.
What the hell are you talking about?

992
01:01:54,627 --> 01:01:56,461
I don't know. I shouldn't have--

993
01:01:56,629 --> 01:01:59,131
I'm not gonna do this.
I think this is stupid.

994
01:01:59,298 --> 01:02:02,467
I'm not gonna fire anybody,
and this is dumb.

995
01:02:03,553 --> 01:02:06,805
They're professional ballplayers.
Just be straight with them.

996
01:02:06,973 --> 01:02:08,932
No fluff, just facts.

997
01:02:09,100 --> 01:02:13,937
Pete, I gotta let you go.
Jack's office will handle the details.

998
01:02:16,649 --> 01:02:19,067
That's it?
Pfft.

999
01:02:19,277 --> 01:02:20,318
Really?

1000
01:02:20,486 --> 01:02:24,906
You rather get a bullet
to the head or five to the
chest and bleed to death?

1001
01:02:26,492 --> 01:02:29,161
Are those
my only two options?

1002
01:02:29,328 --> 01:02:31,496
Go on the road with the team.

1003
01:02:34,125 --> 01:02:35,751
Okay.

1004
01:02:45,094 --> 01:02:46,636
Say, bro.

1005
01:02:46,804 --> 01:02:48,847
Let me ask you a question.
Yeah.

1006
01:02:49,015 --> 01:02:51,850
How come your boss
doesn't travel with the team?

1007
01:02:53,728 --> 01:02:57,314
He doesn't like to mingle
with the players.

1008
01:02:59,108 --> 01:03:01,693
Is that supposed to
make us easier to cut?

1009
01:03:06,908 --> 01:03:09,034
I don't know. I don't know.

1010
01:03:09,202 --> 01:03:14,039
And how come soda
is a dollar in the clubhouse?

1011
01:03:14,207 --> 01:03:16,458
I never seen
nothing like that.

1012
01:03:17,710 --> 01:03:20,545
Billy likes to keep
the money on the field.

1013
01:03:20,713 --> 01:03:22,589
Soda money?

1014
01:03:23,049 --> 01:03:24,591
Really?

1015
01:03:25,092 --> 01:03:28,512
Where on the field is the
dollar I'm paying for soda?

1016
01:03:30,097 --> 01:03:33,558
It's hard to see exactly,

1017
01:03:33,726 --> 01:03:36,686
but it's there, yeah.
Yeah, it is hard to see.

1018
01:03:37,313 --> 01:03:38,897
I'm done.

1019
01:03:40,441 --> 01:03:42,442
[♪♪♪]

1020
01:03:50,034 --> 01:03:52,786
Hey, Dad.
Hi, honey.

1021
01:03:52,954 --> 01:03:54,955
How are you?
I'm good.

1022
01:03:55,122 --> 01:03:57,249
Was it bumpy?
It was okay.

1023
01:03:59,710 --> 01:04:02,379
ANNOUNCER:
So with this loss tonight,
the Oakland Athletics

1024
01:04:02,547 --> 01:04:07,634
incredibly, have lost 14
of their last 17 games.

1025
01:04:07,802 --> 01:04:10,887
They are 10 games back
in the American League West.

1026
01:04:11,055 --> 01:04:13,557
HOST: Is it fair to say
the experiment has failed?

1027
01:04:13,724 --> 01:04:16,059
COMMENTATOR 1:
Well, absolutely. It was predictable.

1028
01:04:16,227 --> 01:04:20,689
You don't wish anybody
a lack of success, but the
facts are in front of you.

1029
01:04:20,857 --> 01:04:22,691
COMMENTATOR 2:
You can't blame Art Howe.

1030
01:04:22,859 --> 01:04:23,900
HOST:
No.

1031
01:04:24,068 --> 01:04:28,196
COMMENTATOR 2: The fact
of the matter is, this is not about
statistics, this is about people.

1032
01:04:28,364 --> 01:04:31,116
COMMENTATOR 1:
Art Howe is not the problem.

1033
01:04:31,284 --> 01:04:35,203
The problem is in the
general manager's office
with Billy Beane.

1034
01:04:35,371 --> 01:04:38,039
COMMENTATOR 2:
The root of the problem for me
is philosophical.

1035
01:04:38,207 --> 01:04:40,375
I said it before.
This is fantasy baseball.

1036
01:04:40,877 --> 01:04:42,335
Billy is just not thinking.

1037
01:04:42,503 --> 01:04:45,130
CALLER 1:
Start thinking about a new GM,
making changes.

1038
01:04:45,298 --> 01:04:46,882
CALLER 2:
He never goes to the games.

1039
01:04:47,049 --> 01:04:48,508
GRADY:
This was very predictable.

1040
01:04:48,676 --> 01:04:51,303
CALLER 2:
He needs to look at what's going on.

1041
01:04:51,470 --> 01:04:54,931
The man needs to get real.
CALLER 3: I want Billy Beane gone.

1042
01:04:55,099 --> 01:04:57,559
HOST:
Calling for Beane's head.
I want your thoughts.

1043
01:04:57,727 --> 01:05:02,939
ANNOUNCER:
The past 18 games, they've been
shut out or scored one run four times.

1044
01:05:03,107 --> 01:05:04,816
They're just not scoring enough.

1045
01:05:04,984 --> 01:05:08,153
It's not just the offense,
not Thad Bosley and the hitters.

1046
01:05:08,321 --> 01:05:12,616
It's everything. If there was one thing
you could pick out, you'd try to fix it,

1047
01:05:12,783 --> 01:05:18,121
but just everything is in a funk
right now.

1048
01:05:18,289 --> 01:05:20,290
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

1049
01:05:22,710 --> 01:05:25,295
What the hell am I doing?

1050
01:05:27,673 --> 01:05:30,425
Oh, man.

1051
01:05:30,593 --> 01:05:32,594
BILLY:
Look, Steve.

1052
01:05:36,140 --> 01:05:38,266
I believe in what
we're doing.

1053
01:05:38,434 --> 01:05:41,311
The record doesn't reflect
the strength of this team

1054
01:05:41,479 --> 01:05:44,189
or where we're gonna be
at the end of the season.

1055
01:05:44,357 --> 01:05:48,985
Now, Pete and I here feel
very strongly that we stay
on the track we've chosen.

1056
01:05:49,153 --> 01:05:51,696
PETER:
Our sample size has
been too small. It's too--

1057
01:05:51,864 --> 01:05:53,531
BILLY:
Early. It's still early.

1058
01:05:54,200 --> 01:05:57,285
Where do we expect to be
by the All-Star break?

1059
01:05:58,454 --> 01:06:00,956
Our goal
and our expectation

1060
01:06:01,123 --> 01:06:04,876
is by mid-July to be within
seven games of first.

1061
01:06:05,044 --> 01:06:06,503
That would be
this working.

1062
01:06:06,671 --> 01:06:09,172
That keeps us in the hunt.
Exceptionally well.

1063
01:06:09,715 --> 01:06:12,592
By July.
BILLY: July.

1064
01:06:12,760 --> 01:06:16,638
And what's gonna prevent you
from accomplishing that?

1065
01:06:16,806 --> 01:06:18,473
What are you afraid of?

1066
01:06:18,641 --> 01:06:21,559
BILLY:
Nothing. That's why
we're here, Steve.

1067
01:06:21,727 --> 01:06:25,063
That's why we get up
in the morning.
That's all we do.

1068
01:06:44,625 --> 01:06:46,167
More?
Yeah, a little more.

1069
01:06:46,335 --> 01:06:49,796
Don't tell your mother.
I won't.

1070
01:06:50,548 --> 01:06:52,674
Chocolate sauce?
Yes.

1071
01:06:53,509 --> 01:06:54,926
Stop.

1072
01:06:57,513 --> 01:07:00,473
Big spoon or little spoon?
Little spoon.

1073
01:07:01,851 --> 01:07:03,518
Thank you.

1074
01:07:13,195 --> 01:07:16,031
Dad, there's no way you're
gonna lose your job, right?

1075
01:07:16,198 --> 01:07:17,240
What?

1076
01:07:18,784 --> 01:07:19,909
Well, I don't know.

1077
01:07:20,077 --> 01:07:22,162
I'm just wondering.
Where'd you hear that?

1078
01:07:22,329 --> 01:07:24,289
Well, I go on the Internet
sometimes.

1079
01:07:24,457 --> 01:07:27,625
Well, don't do that.
Don't go on the Internet.

1080
01:07:27,793 --> 01:07:30,628
Or watch TV
or read newspapers

1081
01:07:31,422 --> 01:07:33,339
or talk to people.

1082
01:07:33,507 --> 01:07:36,176
I don't talk to people.
I just read stuff.

1083
01:07:36,343 --> 01:07:38,970
Honey, everything's fine.
Everything's fine.

1084
01:07:39,722 --> 01:07:41,598
Really, you don't have to worry.

1085
01:07:41,766 --> 01:07:45,143
But if you lose your job,
will you have to move away?

1086
01:07:45,895 --> 01:07:48,313
Honey, I'm not gonna
lose my job.

1087
01:07:49,732 --> 01:07:51,733
You don't have to worry.

1088
01:07:54,111 --> 01:07:56,488
Okay.
Hey.

1089
01:07:57,073 --> 01:08:00,450
There's no problem.
Okay.

1090
01:08:00,618 --> 01:08:03,953
All right? I got uptown problems,
which are not problems at all.

1091
01:08:04,955 --> 01:08:06,331
You're not worried, right?

1092
01:08:06,499 --> 01:08:09,000
No, I'm not worried.
Okay.

1093
01:08:16,300 --> 01:08:17,967
Pena.

1094
01:08:20,638 --> 01:08:22,263
Okay.

1095
01:08:35,069 --> 01:08:37,195
I want Dye in right,

1096
01:08:37,363 --> 01:08:40,198
Justice DH'ing,
Pena on the bench,

1097
01:08:40,366 --> 01:08:42,158
Hatteberg at first,

1098
01:08:42,326 --> 01:08:45,370
and anyone but Mags
first out of the pen.

1099
01:08:45,538 --> 01:08:47,455
You want Pena on the bench?

1100
01:08:47,623 --> 01:08:50,750
That's right.
So you can play Hattie.

1101
01:08:50,918 --> 01:08:53,169
Pena is not only
the best first baseman,

1102
01:08:53,337 --> 01:08:55,505
he's the only first baseman.

1103
01:08:55,673 --> 01:08:58,049
Hattie gets on base
more than Pena.

1104
01:08:58,217 --> 01:09:00,718
In fact, 20 percent more.
And his fielding?

1105
01:09:00,886 --> 01:09:03,555
His fielding does not matter.

1106
01:09:04,557 --> 01:09:06,808
I've heard enough of this.
Have you?

1107
01:09:06,976 --> 01:09:08,560
And I, uh...

1108
01:09:09,395 --> 01:09:12,397
I disagree with you,
plain and simple.

1109
01:09:13,315 --> 01:09:15,483
And moreover,
I'm playing my team

1110
01:09:15,985 --> 01:09:19,654
in a way that I can explain
in job interviews next winter.

1111
01:09:20,573 --> 01:09:22,240
Okay? Ahem.

1112
01:09:27,246 --> 01:09:30,248
Hattie. Not Pena.

1113
01:09:34,587 --> 01:09:35,962
What's up, skip?

1114
01:09:36,130 --> 01:09:38,590
How you doing?
Good, how you doing, man?

1115
01:09:38,757 --> 01:09:40,383
Get some sleep
last night?

1116
01:09:42,511 --> 01:09:45,597
ANNOUNCER [ON TV]:
As the A's hit the field,
we are ready for baseball.

1117
01:09:45,764 --> 01:09:49,100
First one out of the dugout
is rookie sensation Carlos Pena,

1118
01:09:49,268 --> 01:09:53,563
one of the few bright lights in this
lineup, taking his spot at first base.

1119
01:09:53,731 --> 01:09:55,315
[CHAIR CLATTERING]

1120
01:09:56,233 --> 01:09:58,234
[♪♪♪]

1121
01:10:01,280 --> 01:10:03,281
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

1122
01:10:22,176 --> 01:10:26,179
[PARLIAMENT'S "GIVE UP THE
FUNK (TEAR THE ROOF OFF THE
SUCKER)" PLAYING ON STEREO]

1123
01:10:26,388 --> 01:10:30,099
♪ Down, gettin' down
There's a whole lot of rhythm ♪

1124
01:10:33,979 --> 01:10:37,565
Billy, quick question.
Do you expect these guys
to produce more or--?

1125
01:10:37,733 --> 01:10:39,943
BILLY: Not now.
What's the reason for the slump?

1126
01:10:40,110 --> 01:10:41,569
♪ We gotta have the funk ♪

1127
01:10:41,737 --> 01:10:44,405
♪ Ow, we want the funk ♪

1128
01:10:44,573 --> 01:10:45,949
♪ Give up the funk ♪

1129
01:10:46,116 --> 01:10:48,326
♪ Ow, we need the funk ♪

1130
01:10:49,161 --> 01:10:50,995
♪ We gotta have the funk ♪♪

1131
01:10:51,997 --> 01:10:53,331
[MUSIC STOPS]

1132
01:10:58,337 --> 01:10:59,879
Get down.

1133
01:11:04,051 --> 01:11:06,010
Is losing fun?

1134
01:11:09,223 --> 01:11:12,350
Is losing fun?
No.

1135
01:11:16,480 --> 01:11:18,690
What are you having fun for?

1136
01:11:27,866 --> 01:11:29,534
[BAT CLATTERS]

1137
01:11:44,091 --> 01:11:46,509
That's what losing
sounds like.

1138
01:12:01,066 --> 01:12:02,483
Are you okay, Dad?

1139
01:12:03,235 --> 01:12:05,194
You're doing it again.
What?

1140
01:12:05,362 --> 01:12:07,655
You're worrying about me.

1141
01:12:07,865 --> 01:12:09,699
You're in last place, Dad.

1142
01:12:09,867 --> 01:12:12,243
Do I look worried?
Yeah.

1143
01:12:12,411 --> 01:12:16,372
Because you're getting
on an airplane, and those
things crash all the time.

1144
01:12:16,540 --> 01:12:18,958
Please stop worrying
about your dad.

1145
01:12:21,253 --> 01:12:22,879
We're all set.
Okay.

1146
01:12:24,757 --> 01:12:26,924
I love you.
Love you too.

1147
01:12:27,384 --> 01:12:30,261
All right. Your dad's not in trouble.

1148
01:12:31,305 --> 01:12:33,264
Okay.

1149
01:12:37,603 --> 01:12:39,604
[♪♪♪]

1150
01:12:57,289 --> 01:12:59,624
[TIRES SCREECHING]

1151
01:13:12,179 --> 01:13:13,971
Yeah.

1152
01:13:19,978 --> 01:13:22,146
Suzanne, get me Ed Wade.
SUZANNE: Okay.

1153
01:13:22,314 --> 01:13:24,023
Coffee on?
Yes.

1154
01:13:24,191 --> 01:13:26,818
Good morning.
Good morning, Billy.

1155
01:13:30,406 --> 01:13:32,240
Oh, hi, Louisa.

1156
01:13:32,408 --> 01:13:35,326
I need Ed Wade for Billy Beane.
PETER: Hi.

1157
01:13:36,495 --> 01:13:37,537
SUZANNE:
Please hold.

1158
01:13:37,704 --> 01:13:40,331
PETER: What's up?
SUZANNE: Wade's on 2.

1159
01:13:40,499 --> 01:13:41,958
Ed?
WADE [OVER SPEAKER]: Hello?

1160
01:13:42,126 --> 01:13:44,544
Ed, it's Billy.
Billy, what's up?

1161
01:13:44,711 --> 01:13:47,713
Look, I need a little help on defense.
Okay.

1162
01:13:47,881 --> 01:13:50,466
I'm willing to trade
Jeremy Giambi for it.

1163
01:13:51,176 --> 01:13:52,635
Really?
What?

1164
01:13:52,803 --> 01:13:54,929
Mm-hm. Who you got?
What?

1165
01:13:55,097 --> 01:13:58,266
Well, let me think.
What are you doing?

1166
01:13:58,434 --> 01:13:59,684
Cleaning house.

1167
01:13:59,852 --> 01:14:01,811
Mabry?
Maybe what?

1168
01:14:01,979 --> 01:14:05,022
No, Mabry.
Hold on.

1169
01:14:05,190 --> 01:14:07,024
No.
Why not?

1170
01:14:07,192 --> 01:14:09,360
Because you can't trade
Jeremy Giambi.

1171
01:14:10,612 --> 01:14:12,113
He'll be fine, Ed.

1172
01:14:12,281 --> 01:14:14,866
Why do I get the feeling
you're picking my pocket?

1173
01:14:15,033 --> 01:14:18,369
I'm not. You're picking mine.
Giambi's name alone is worth more.

1174
01:14:18,537 --> 01:14:20,746
What's wrong with him?
Nothing.

1175
01:14:20,914 --> 01:14:24,417
Can we say it's done in theory
and start drawing up the paperwork?

1176
01:14:24,585 --> 01:14:26,836
Okay, but you're gonna have--
Great.

1177
01:14:27,004 --> 01:14:28,713
He was gonna
say something else.

1178
01:14:28,881 --> 01:14:31,466
When you get the answer
you're looking for, hang up.

1179
01:14:31,633 --> 01:14:32,675
Suzanne.
SUZANNE: Yes?

1180
01:14:32,843 --> 01:14:35,303
David Dombrowski.
SUZANNE: Okay.

1181
01:14:35,471 --> 01:14:38,431
And Pena's going too.
I don't think you should do that.

1182
01:14:38,599 --> 01:14:40,558
I really don't think
you should do that.

1183
01:14:40,726 --> 01:14:43,060
I want Hatteberg
in the lineup tonight.

1184
01:14:43,228 --> 01:14:44,604
You need to take a minute.

1185
01:14:44,771 --> 01:14:47,899
I think you seriously need
to think about what you're doing.

1186
01:14:48,066 --> 01:14:50,568
Because you're upset.
Okay.

1187
01:14:51,069 --> 01:14:52,904
What am I missing?

1188
01:14:53,572 --> 01:14:55,907
These are hard moves
to explain to people.

1189
01:14:56,783 --> 01:14:58,409
Why is that a problem, Pete?

1190
01:15:01,205 --> 01:15:03,414
Don't make
an emotional decision, Billy.

1191
01:15:03,582 --> 01:15:05,416
SUZANNE:
David Dombrowski's on 3.

1192
01:15:05,584 --> 01:15:07,960
Look, we're gonna
shake things up.

1193
01:15:08,128 --> 01:15:11,172
Dave. Pena's going on the block.
You're my first call.

1194
01:15:12,174 --> 01:15:14,967
Because he's making the rest
of the team look bad.

1195
01:15:15,928 --> 01:15:17,762
He's gonna be
a Rookie of the Year.

1196
01:15:17,930 --> 01:15:21,098
Probably an All-Star.
He's an All-Star, Dave.

1197
01:15:21,975 --> 01:15:24,769
No. I want a reliever and cash.

1198
01:15:25,270 --> 01:15:28,940
Okay. You got five minutes, Dave.
I'm not waiting.

1199
01:15:29,650 --> 01:15:33,444
Billy, Pena is an All-Star, okay?

1200
01:15:33,612 --> 01:15:39,534
And if you dump him and this
Hatteberg thing doesn't work out,
you know this is--

1201
01:15:39,701 --> 01:15:42,787
This is the kind of decision
that gets you fired.

1202
01:15:42,955 --> 01:15:44,539
It is.

1203
01:15:45,082 --> 01:15:47,124
Yes, you're right.

1204
01:15:47,584 --> 01:15:49,877
I may lose my job.

1205
01:15:50,045 --> 01:15:53,464
In which case I'm a 44-year-old guy
with a high school diploma

1206
01:15:53,632 --> 01:15:56,926
and a daughter
I'd like to be able to send to college.

1207
01:15:57,427 --> 01:16:00,471
You're 25 years old,
with a degree from Yale

1208
01:16:00,639 --> 01:16:03,224
and a pretty impressive
apprenticeship.

1209
01:16:04,059 --> 01:16:06,811
I don't think
we're asking the right question.

1210
01:16:07,312 --> 01:16:10,314
I think the question
we should be asking is,

1211
01:16:10,482 --> 01:16:13,150
do you believe in this thing
or not?

1212
01:16:14,987 --> 01:16:16,571
I do.

1213
01:16:19,616 --> 01:16:22,660
It's a problem you think
we need to explain ourselves.

1214
01:16:22,828 --> 01:16:26,038
Don't. To anyone.

1215
01:16:29,418 --> 01:16:30,876
Okay.

1216
01:16:33,422 --> 01:16:36,882
Now, I'm gonna see this thing
through, for better or worse.

1217
01:16:40,345 --> 01:16:45,182
Just tell me, do you project we'll win
more with Hatteberg or Pena at first?

1218
01:16:45,767 --> 01:16:48,185
It's close...

1219
01:16:49,021 --> 01:16:51,439
but theoretically, Hatteberg.

1220
01:16:52,316 --> 01:16:54,108
What are we talking about, then?

1221
01:16:54,276 --> 01:16:57,320
SUZANNE:
Dombrowski's on again, on 3.

1222
01:16:59,656 --> 01:17:01,073
Yeah?

1223
01:17:01,783 --> 01:17:03,701
Okay, that'll work.

1224
01:17:04,369 --> 01:17:06,621
Great. I need one more thing.

1225
01:17:06,788 --> 01:17:10,041
Soda. Yeah, I don't want
my guys paying for soda.

1226
01:17:10,208 --> 01:17:12,877
I want you to stock
my machine for three years.

1227
01:17:13,045 --> 01:17:14,545
I'm serious.

1228
01:17:15,547 --> 01:17:17,548
Great. It's a deal.

1229
01:17:18,675 --> 01:17:20,635
Go tell Pena he's gotta pack.

1230
01:17:22,137 --> 01:17:25,348
You want me to tell Pena?
Part of the job.

1231
01:17:27,851 --> 01:17:30,269
What about Giambi?
You want me to tell him too?

1232
01:17:30,437 --> 01:17:32,396
I'll tell him.

1233
01:17:39,363 --> 01:17:40,946
Excuse me, Carlos?
Yeah?

1234
01:17:41,114 --> 01:17:43,074
Can I speak with you a minute?
Yeah.

1235
01:17:51,833 --> 01:17:54,418
Carlos, you've been
traded to the Tigers.

1236
01:17:57,923 --> 01:17:59,924
This is Jay Palmer's number.

1237
01:18:00,092 --> 01:18:02,635
He's the traveling secretary
for the team.

1238
01:18:02,803 --> 01:18:05,846
He's expecting your call.
He'll take care of everything.

1239
01:18:15,107 --> 01:18:17,608
Is that it?
Yes.

1240
01:18:24,908 --> 01:18:26,325
Okay.

1241
01:18:35,961 --> 01:18:37,336
[SIGHS]

1242
01:18:38,672 --> 01:18:40,131
Okay.

1243
01:18:42,718 --> 01:18:43,926
Art, you got a minute?

1244
01:18:47,180 --> 01:18:50,224
Yeah. Take a seat.

1245
01:18:53,645 --> 01:18:57,982
You can't start Pena at first tonight.
You'll have to start Hatteberg.

1246
01:18:58,817 --> 01:19:00,985
I don't wanna go
15 rounds, Billy.

1247
01:19:01,153 --> 01:19:03,821
The lineup card is mine,
and that's all.

1248
01:19:03,989 --> 01:19:05,990
BILLY:
That lineup card is definitely yours.

1249
01:19:06,158 --> 01:19:08,743
I'm just saying
you can't start Pena at first.

1250
01:19:09,077 --> 01:19:10,411
Well...

1251
01:19:11,830 --> 01:19:13,998
I am starting him at first.

1252
01:19:14,166 --> 01:19:18,127
BILLY: I don't think so.
He plays for Detroit now.

1253
01:19:22,048 --> 01:19:24,216
You traded Pena?

1254
01:19:25,385 --> 01:19:26,927
Yeah.

1255
01:19:27,095 --> 01:19:31,515
And Menechino, Hiljus, Tam
are all being sent down.

1256
01:19:31,683 --> 01:19:35,978
You are outside your mind.
BILLY: Yeah. Cuckoo.

1257
01:19:37,773 --> 01:19:40,566
You wanted to see me?
Yeah, Jeremy, grab a seat.

1258
01:19:44,154 --> 01:19:46,655
Jeremy, you've been
traded to the Phillies.

1259
01:19:46,823 --> 01:19:49,450
This is Ed Wade's number.
He's a good guy, the GM.

1260
01:19:49,618 --> 01:19:51,952
He's expecting your call.

1261
01:19:52,120 --> 01:19:54,955
Buddy will help you
with the plane flight.

1262
01:19:56,291 --> 01:19:59,001
You're a good ballplayer,
Jeremy,

1263
01:19:59,169 --> 01:20:01,712
and we wish you the best.

1264
01:20:03,799 --> 01:20:05,382
[JEREMY SIGHS]

1265
01:20:18,230 --> 01:20:20,314
Jeremy's gone too.

1266
01:20:22,275 --> 01:20:24,401
You're killing this team.

1267
01:20:24,569 --> 01:20:28,239
Art, I can do this all day long.

1268
01:20:34,371 --> 01:20:35,746
ART:
Hey.

1269
01:20:36,706 --> 01:20:38,749
You agree with this?

1270
01:20:40,126 --> 01:20:41,836
Hundred percent.

1271
01:20:43,380 --> 01:20:44,922
You want this door closed?

1272
01:20:48,051 --> 01:20:50,052
[♪♪♪]

1273
01:20:52,931 --> 01:20:55,266
[PLAYERS CHATTERING]

1274
01:20:57,477 --> 01:20:59,937
Scotty H.
Sir?

1275
01:21:00,939 --> 01:21:04,608
Go field some grounders.
Yes, sir.

1276
01:21:04,776 --> 01:21:06,610
Everybody, listen up.

1277
01:21:09,614 --> 01:21:12,366
You may not look
like a winning team...

1278
01:21:15,620 --> 01:21:17,705
but you are one.

1279
01:21:22,085 --> 01:21:23,419
So...

1280
01:21:25,005 --> 01:21:27,047
play like one tonight.

1281
01:21:35,682 --> 01:21:37,892
Oh, shit.

1282
01:21:40,979 --> 01:21:44,148
When you're getting your pitch,
you're hitting .625, massive.

1283
01:21:44,316 --> 01:21:46,150
You're crushing the ball.

1284
01:21:46,318 --> 01:21:49,194
But when you swing at things--
Your pitch is middle-in.

1285
01:21:49,362 --> 01:21:52,239
When you're
swinging low and away,
you're batting .158.

1286
01:21:52,407 --> 01:21:54,491
Every at bat's
like a hand of blackjack.

1287
01:21:54,659 --> 01:21:56,994
Every card that's dealt,
your odds change.

1288
01:21:57,162 --> 01:22:01,498
So every first-pitch strike,
your batting average goes
down about 75 points.

1289
01:22:01,666 --> 01:22:02,833
Seventy-five points.

1290
01:22:03,001 --> 01:22:05,252
He should throw 100
pitches before the fifth.

1291
01:22:05,420 --> 01:22:07,171
You wanna knock
that starter out.

1292
01:22:07,339 --> 01:22:10,841
I want you taking at bats off the 10th
and 11th pitcher by the end.

1293
01:22:11,009 --> 01:22:13,427
This is your basic breakdown
of the pitches,

1294
01:22:13,595 --> 01:22:15,804
where you should
be hitting them, why.

1295
01:22:15,972 --> 01:22:19,516
So you want us to walk more?
Good question. Yes.

1296
01:22:20,936 --> 01:22:23,020
Mr. Justice.

1297
01:22:23,188 --> 01:22:25,147
Had a few thoughts.
Yeah?

1298
01:22:25,315 --> 01:22:27,691
Yeah.
Gonna teach me some things?

1299
01:22:28,151 --> 01:22:29,860
Excuse me?

1300
01:22:31,404 --> 01:22:33,697
Never seen a GM
talk to players like that.

1301
01:22:33,865 --> 01:22:36,533
You never seen a GM
who was a player.

1302
01:22:38,286 --> 01:22:39,662
Huh.

1303
01:22:40,914 --> 01:22:42,456
[BAT CRACKS]

1304
01:22:42,832 --> 01:22:45,626
We got a problem, David?
No, it's okay.

1305
01:22:45,794 --> 01:22:48,003
I know your routine.

1306
01:22:48,171 --> 01:22:50,464
It's patter. It's for effect.

1307
01:22:50,632 --> 01:22:51,840
[BAT CRACKS]

1308
01:22:52,717 --> 01:22:56,887
But it's for them, all right?
That shit ain't for me.

1309
01:22:57,389 --> 01:22:59,139
Oh, you're special?

1310
01:23:01,559 --> 01:23:06,188
You're paying me 7 million bucks
a year, man, so, yeah,

1311
01:23:06,356 --> 01:23:08,691
maybe I am, a little bit.

1312
01:23:08,858 --> 01:23:11,819
No, man,
I ain't paying you 7.

1313
01:23:12,529 --> 01:23:14,405
Yankees are paying
half your salary.

1314
01:23:14,572 --> 01:23:17,408
That's what the New York Yankees
think of you.

1315
01:23:18,243 --> 01:23:22,579
They're paying you $3.5 million
to play against them.

1316
01:23:23,873 --> 01:23:26,041
Where you going with this, Billy?

1317
01:23:26,835 --> 01:23:29,169
David, you're 37.

1318
01:23:29,337 --> 01:23:33,090
How about you and I be honest about
what each of us want out of this?

1319
01:23:34,718 --> 01:23:38,095
I wanna milk the last ounce
of baseball you got in you.

1320
01:23:38,263 --> 01:23:40,556
And you wanna stay in the show.

1321
01:23:41,099 --> 01:23:43,058
Let's do that.

1322
01:23:43,935 --> 01:23:46,520
I'm not paying you
for the player you used to be.

1323
01:23:46,688 --> 01:23:49,690
I'm paying you for the player
you are right now.

1324
01:23:49,858 --> 01:23:53,277
You're smart. You get what
we're trying to do here.

1325
01:23:53,445 --> 01:23:56,280
Make an example
for the younger guys.

1326
01:23:56,448 --> 01:23:58,240
Be a leader.

1327
01:23:58,908 --> 01:24:00,576
Can you do that?

1328
01:24:07,667 --> 01:24:10,627
All right. I got you.

1329
01:24:13,089 --> 01:24:14,798
We're cool?

1330
01:24:16,885 --> 01:24:18,343
We're cool.

1331
01:24:23,641 --> 01:24:24,850
Scotty H.

1332
01:24:25,018 --> 01:24:27,144
Yo, what's up, D.J.?
Picking machine.

1333
01:24:27,312 --> 01:24:28,353
[CHUCKLES]

1334
01:24:28,521 --> 01:24:30,731
How you liking
first base, man?

1335
01:24:32,025 --> 01:24:35,235
It's coming along.
Picking it up.

1336
01:24:35,403 --> 01:24:39,531
You know, tough transition,
but I'm starting to feel better with it.

1337
01:24:39,699 --> 01:24:41,742
Yeah?
Yeah.

1338
01:24:41,910 --> 01:24:43,827
What's your biggest fear?

1339
01:24:44,454 --> 01:24:47,164
A baseball being hit
in my general direction.

1340
01:24:47,332 --> 01:24:49,083
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

1341
01:24:49,250 --> 01:24:52,377
That's funny.
Seriously, what is it?

1342
01:24:55,840 --> 01:24:58,175
No, seriously, that is.

1343
01:25:08,937 --> 01:25:11,271
Well, hey, good luck with that.

1344
01:25:11,439 --> 01:25:13,607
Be social out there.

1345
01:25:14,526 --> 01:25:17,069
Social.
Social. Like a greeter at the Gap.

1346
01:25:17,237 --> 01:25:19,321
Guy steps into your office,
chat him up.

1347
01:25:19,489 --> 01:25:22,157
You're well-read.
You went to school.

1348
01:25:22,325 --> 01:25:24,493
Yeah.
Have some fun. Relax.

1349
01:25:24,661 --> 01:25:27,538
Everyone wants to attack.
Quit trying to attack.

1350
01:25:27,705 --> 01:25:30,958
Let the game come to you, man.
There's no clock on this thing.

1351
01:25:31,126 --> 01:25:32,543
This is a war of attrition.

1352
01:25:32,710 --> 01:25:37,131
If I take more, I could
even take a few strikes,
but I'll get walked more.

1353
01:25:37,298 --> 01:25:41,051
You get on base, we win.
You don't, we lose.

1354
01:25:41,219 --> 01:25:44,555
And I hate losing,
Chavvie. I hate it.

1355
01:25:44,722 --> 01:25:47,307
I hate losing more
than I even wanna win.

1356
01:25:47,475 --> 01:25:48,809
And there's
a difference.

1357
01:25:48,977 --> 01:25:50,477
No bunts.
Bunts is an out.

1358
01:25:50,645 --> 01:25:53,897
Even if the third baseman is back?
No bunting whatsoever.

1359
01:25:54,065 --> 01:25:56,817
If someone bunts on us,
throw it to first.

1360
01:25:56,985 --> 01:25:58,735
Don't be a hero
and go to second.

1361
01:25:58,903 --> 01:26:00,320
Let them make the mistakes.

1362
01:26:00,488 --> 01:26:03,407
When your enemy's
making mistakes,
don't interrupt them.

1363
01:26:03,575 --> 01:26:06,118
They're giving you an out.
Just giving it to you.

1364
01:26:06,286 --> 01:26:07,578
Take it.
Say thank you.

1365
01:26:07,745 --> 01:26:09,746
Another thing.
No more stealing.

1366
01:26:09,914 --> 01:26:11,957
That's what I do,
what you pay me to do.

1367
01:26:12,125 --> 01:26:15,085
I pay you to get on first,
not get thrown out at second.

1368
01:26:15,253 --> 01:26:20,215
This is a process.
It's a process,
it's a process. Okay?

1369
01:26:20,383 --> 01:26:22,342
[♪♪♪]

1370
01:26:32,562 --> 01:26:36,440
ANNOUNCER 1:
Jason takes it, goes to second for
the only out, and the A's get a run.

1371
01:26:38,067 --> 01:26:42,154
ANNOUNCER 2:
Jermaine Dye homers again,
his second in two games.

1372
01:26:42,322 --> 01:26:46,783
And the A's are still hanging in.
We'll get you scores here.

1373
01:26:46,951 --> 01:26:51,413
The A's pull within two of the
Angels for the wild-card chase.

1374
01:26:51,581 --> 01:26:53,749
ANNOUNCER 3:
The Reds have now dropped
five in a row

1375
01:26:53,917 --> 01:26:57,294
as Oakland beats them
in the beginning of this series 5 to 3.

1376
01:26:57,462 --> 01:26:58,795
ANNOUNCER 2:
Tejada walks.

1377
01:26:58,963 --> 01:27:00,297
Ball four.

1378
01:27:00,465 --> 01:27:03,342
ANNOUNCER 4:
Ball four and Hatteberg walks.

1379
01:27:04,886 --> 01:27:08,388
ANNOUNCER 5:
What is happening in Oakland?
The A's have won seven in a row.

1380
01:27:08,556 --> 01:27:10,807
A lot of excitement.
What a winning streak.

1381
01:27:10,975 --> 01:27:13,810
But how about the calming
influence of Art Howe?

1382
01:27:13,978 --> 01:27:17,606
When you say "your source,"
if it's not me or Peter,
they don't know.

1383
01:27:17,774 --> 01:27:19,483
ANNOUNCER 5 [ON TV]:
He's managing
an unorthodox team.

1384
01:27:19,651 --> 01:27:21,443
BILLY: Right.
It's not a perfect roster.

1385
01:27:21,611 --> 01:27:24,905
But right now, Art Howe is
the reason this team is winning.

1386
01:27:25,073 --> 01:27:27,658
He deserves the credit.
Great, thanks. Bye.

1387
01:27:27,825 --> 01:27:29,368
Did you hear that?

1388
01:27:29,535 --> 01:27:32,496
I heard "seven in a row."
You get the Cleveland matchups?

1389
01:27:32,664 --> 01:27:34,581
Yeah, right here.

1390
01:27:34,749 --> 01:27:36,750
[♪♪♪]

1391
01:27:42,340 --> 01:27:43,799
Voos.
Billy.

1392
01:27:43,967 --> 01:27:47,219
That smell is getting worse.
I'm on it.

1393
01:27:47,971 --> 01:27:50,138
What are we doing?
Splitting it in half?

1394
01:27:50,306 --> 01:27:52,140
Both sides of the plate.
Got it.

1395
01:27:52,850 --> 01:27:55,018
Huddy. Mix it up.
Yes, sir.

1396
01:27:55,186 --> 01:27:57,354
Trust your slider, yeah?
Yes, sir.

1397
01:27:57,522 --> 01:27:59,523
You guys quit distracting him.

1398
01:27:59,691 --> 01:28:02,401
You couldn't hit that shit
last night with a paddle.

1399
01:28:02,568 --> 01:28:04,403
You gotta see more pitches.

1400
01:28:04,570 --> 01:28:07,072
All right, Billy.
Patience.

1401
01:28:10,868 --> 01:28:12,494
Hey, David.
Hey, Billy.

1402
01:28:12,662 --> 01:28:14,037
Great at bats.
Thank you.

1403
01:28:14,205 --> 01:28:15,747
Really quality.
Thank you.

1404
01:28:15,915 --> 01:28:18,625
ANNOUNCER 1 [ON TV]:
Base hit to right field.
Tejada scores.

1405
01:28:18,793 --> 01:28:21,670
Chavez coming in.
The ball gets past Guiel.

1406
01:28:22,588 --> 01:28:26,717
The A's, from 5-nothing down,
now lead 6 to 5.

1407
01:28:36,728 --> 01:28:39,730
ANNOUNCER 2:
The Oakland A's are completely
out of hand at the moment.

1408
01:28:39,897 --> 01:28:42,566
They are an AL-best 17 and 4
this month.

1409
01:28:42,734 --> 01:28:46,528
They also took back-to-back series
at Boston and at New York.

1410
01:28:46,696 --> 01:28:49,323
Remember when they traded
Jeremy Giambi in June

1411
01:28:49,490 --> 01:28:51,825
and everyone thought
they'd just given up?

1412
01:28:51,993 --> 01:28:54,661
Actually, not so much.

1413
01:28:54,829 --> 01:28:56,830
[CHATTERING]

1414
01:28:58,750 --> 01:29:01,251
BILLY:
Suzanne, get Shapiro on the phone.

1415
01:29:01,753 --> 01:29:04,921
You thinking Rincon?
His season's done. He's lost faith.

1416
01:29:05,089 --> 01:29:08,091
I think he's gonna dump him.
Hard-core.

1417
01:29:08,259 --> 01:29:10,552
SUZANNE:
Shapiro on 2.

1418
01:29:12,096 --> 01:29:13,889
Mark, Billy. Let's be honest.

1419
01:29:14,057 --> 01:29:17,434
A premier setup man
isn't gonna get you closer
to the play-offs.

1420
01:29:17,602 --> 01:29:19,519
MARK [OVER SPEAKER]:
Are you referring to Rincon?

1421
01:29:19,687 --> 01:29:21,688
He's a luxury
you can't afford, man.

1422
01:29:21,856 --> 01:29:24,566
And you can?
There's half a million
on his contract.

1423
01:29:24,734 --> 01:29:26,777
And we've got
at least one other suitor.

1424
01:29:26,944 --> 01:29:29,654
By "at least one," you mean one.

1425
01:29:29,822 --> 01:29:32,282
Who is it?
I'd rather not say.

1426
01:29:32,450 --> 01:29:34,785
San Francisco.
San Francisco.

1427
01:29:34,952 --> 01:29:36,453
I'll call you back.

1428
01:29:38,247 --> 01:29:40,415
What do you think
we can get for Magnante?

1429
01:29:40,583 --> 01:29:41,833
Nothing.

1430
01:29:42,752 --> 01:29:45,796
What's left on Venafro's contract?
Two seventy-five.

1431
01:29:46,631 --> 01:29:48,423
Suzanne,
get me Sabean on the line.

1432
01:29:48,591 --> 01:29:52,677
Get the Giants interested
in Venafro, Mark's only got
one buyer for Rincon.

1433
01:29:52,845 --> 01:29:54,304
Us.
SUZANNE: On 3.

1434
01:29:56,349 --> 01:29:59,810
Saby-Sabster, it's Billy.
What do you think of Venafro?

1435
01:29:59,977 --> 01:30:02,145
I can let you have him
for almost nothing.

1436
01:30:02,313 --> 01:30:04,898
SABEAN: Why would you do that?
Because I'm amazing.

1437
01:30:05,066 --> 01:30:07,067
I want a couple bucks
and a sweetener.

1438
01:30:07,485 --> 01:30:09,319
Throw in, say...

1439
01:30:09,487 --> 01:30:11,655
Anderson.
Anderson.

1440
01:30:11,823 --> 01:30:14,783
I like Anderson.
No, you don't. Nobody likes him.

1441
01:30:14,951 --> 01:30:17,494
I don't know why I'm doing this.
But let's do it.

1442
01:30:17,662 --> 01:30:20,580
Venafro for Michaelson. Anderson.
I don't know his name.

1443
01:30:20,748 --> 01:30:23,625
I'll think about it.
Think about it and call me back.

1444
01:30:24,168 --> 01:30:26,169
Get Shapiro on.

1445
01:30:34,095 --> 01:30:36,346
SUZANNE:
Shapiro's on 2.

1446
01:30:38,391 --> 01:30:40,350
Mark.
You can't afford him, Billy.

1447
01:30:40,518 --> 01:30:41,601
You sure about that?

1448
01:30:41,769 --> 01:30:44,354
I get the impression
the market for Rincon is softening.

1449
01:30:44,522 --> 01:30:46,148
Huh?
I could be wrong,

1450
01:30:46,315 --> 01:30:47,941
but I'd call whoever's
interested

1451
01:30:48,109 --> 01:30:51,611
and see if they're still interested.
Call me back.

1452
01:30:52,488 --> 01:30:55,866
What about the Mets for Venafro?
You offered him to the Giants.

1453
01:30:56,033 --> 01:30:57,701
Suzanne, Steve Phillips.

1454
01:30:57,869 --> 01:31:02,706
Between Bonds, Kent, Nen, Snow,
San Francisco's never gonna do it.

1455
01:31:03,124 --> 01:31:06,877
Totally agree.
We just need them to cool on Rincon.

1456
01:31:07,044 --> 01:31:10,172
SUZANNE: Phillips on 2.
Steve-o, it's Billy.

1457
01:31:10,339 --> 01:31:14,050
I hear you're looking for a reliever.
I can give you Venafro.

1458
01:31:14,218 --> 01:31:16,845
I can make it quick and easy.
PHILLIPS: What's the angle?

1459
01:31:17,013 --> 01:31:19,890
No angle.
Who am I getting fleeced for?

1460
01:31:20,558 --> 01:31:23,935
Hang on a sec.
Uh, Bennett, maybe?

1461
01:31:24,103 --> 01:31:25,479
How old?
Twenty-six.

1462
01:31:25,646 --> 01:31:27,731
Twenty-six, Double-A? Forget it.

1463
01:31:27,899 --> 01:31:29,983
Duncan, no.

1464
01:31:31,777 --> 01:31:33,528
No. Furbush, no.

1465
01:31:36,199 --> 01:31:39,910
Eckerton? Eckerton? Eckerton.

1466
01:31:40,870 --> 01:31:41,912
Eckerton.

1467
01:31:42,079 --> 01:31:44,498
I like Eckerton.
You don't even know who Eckerton is.

1468
01:31:44,665 --> 01:31:45,707
[PHONE RINGS]

1469
01:31:45,875 --> 01:31:48,418
Is Venafro hurt?
No, he's fine, he's fine.

1470
01:31:48,586 --> 01:31:49,920
It's just an issue for us.

1471
01:31:50,087 --> 01:31:52,756
Last couple times, he got hammered.
Not his fault.

1472
01:31:52,924 --> 01:31:55,091
That was us. We misused him.
It's Steve.

1473
01:31:55,259 --> 01:31:57,260
[WHISPERING] I'm almost done.
Steve Schott.

1474
01:31:57,678 --> 01:32:00,639
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
Look, Steve-o,
let me be straight with you.

1475
01:32:00,806 --> 01:32:03,600
Here's the deal.
I'm getting Rincon.
It's a done deal.

1476
01:32:03,768 --> 01:32:06,853
I heard the Giants--
Giants want Venafro for Michaelson.

1477
01:32:07,021 --> 01:32:08,939
Anderson.
I'd rather deal with you.

1478
01:32:09,106 --> 01:32:12,108
You can give me Eckerton
and $225,000 in cash,

1479
01:32:12,276 --> 01:32:14,319
and the Giants can't.

1480
01:32:15,154 --> 01:32:17,197
I'll think about it.
Think about it.

1481
01:32:17,365 --> 01:32:19,741
But whoever calls me back first
gets Venafro.

1482
01:32:22,161 --> 01:32:23,370
Schott hung up.

1483
01:32:24,830 --> 01:32:28,124
Oh, I want this one.

1484
01:32:36,133 --> 01:32:38,468
Why isn't anybody calling?

1485
01:32:41,264 --> 01:32:43,473
SUZANNE:
Shapiro's on 2.

1486
01:32:44,850 --> 01:32:46,268
Yeah?

1487
01:32:50,439 --> 01:32:53,066
Okay, let me talk to my owner.
I'll call you back.

1488
01:32:53,234 --> 01:32:55,944
Get Steve on the phone.
Schott or Phillips?

1489
01:32:56,112 --> 01:32:58,989
Why would we call Phillips?
Phillips has gotta call us.

1490
01:33:00,157 --> 01:33:02,325
[MUTTERING]

1491
01:33:02,827 --> 01:33:04,578
Tell him I'm on the other line.

1492
01:33:08,332 --> 01:33:12,002
Hi, Mr. Schott, it's Peter Brand.
I apologize for putting you on hold.

1493
01:33:12,169 --> 01:33:16,965
Billy asked me to call you back.
Tell him we want 225,000 for Rincon.

1494
01:33:17,133 --> 01:33:22,178
Billy says he needs $225,000
for Ricardo Rincon.

1495
01:33:22,722 --> 01:33:24,347
Please.

1496
01:33:25,850 --> 01:33:29,144
Yes, I added the "please"
at the end.

1497
01:33:30,521 --> 01:33:33,773
Okay. Let me--
Hold on one second, please.

1498
01:33:34,567 --> 01:33:36,568
[WHISPERING]
Tell him I'll pay for him.

1499
01:33:36,736 --> 01:33:41,072
But when I sell him back for
twice the amount next year,
I keep the money.

1500
01:33:43,034 --> 01:33:46,036
Okay, so Billy says
he'll pay for Rincon himself.

1501
01:33:46,203 --> 01:33:50,498
But when he sells him
for more money next year,
he's keeping the profit.

1502
01:34:00,426 --> 01:34:03,136
Thank you very much.
We'll call you back. Thank you.

1503
01:34:03,304 --> 01:34:05,764
Come on. Come on.

1504
01:34:05,931 --> 01:34:07,849
[BANGING]

1505
01:34:11,062 --> 01:34:14,898
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
Suzanne, call Shapiro ba--
Never mind, I got him right here.

1506
01:34:17,693 --> 01:34:19,486
Mark. Yeah.

1507
01:34:19,654 --> 01:34:22,572
Listen, I don't want Rincon
pitching against me tonight.

1508
01:34:22,740 --> 01:34:26,242
Tell him to change clothes
and send him over.
I got you the money.

1509
01:34:26,410 --> 01:34:27,827
Yup.

1510
01:34:27,995 --> 01:34:29,412
Great.

1511
01:34:33,584 --> 01:34:37,587
I don't wanna dampen
the mood at all, but since
we picked up Rincon...

1512
01:34:37,755 --> 01:34:40,006
We gotta send someone down.

1513
01:34:46,722 --> 01:34:49,766
Mags.
Hey, Billy.

1514
01:34:52,728 --> 01:34:54,604
I know I've been struggling lately.

1515
01:34:54,772 --> 01:34:58,525
But second half of the season,
definitely turn it around. Ricky and I--

1516
01:34:58,693 --> 01:35:02,612
Mike, I need you
to stop getting dressed.

1517
01:35:05,157 --> 01:35:06,783
Traded?

1518
01:35:15,543 --> 01:35:16,960
[SIGHS]

1519
01:35:17,628 --> 01:35:20,046
I'm sorry for the crap news.

1520
01:35:20,798 --> 01:35:22,757
I know it hurts.

1521
01:35:32,977 --> 01:35:35,812
Mike, I can't have 26 guys
in the clubhouse.

1522
01:35:35,980 --> 01:35:38,940
I get it. I get it.

1523
01:35:40,151 --> 01:35:43,361
Okay. Thanks.

1524
01:35:57,626 --> 01:35:58,918
Hey, Ricardo.

1525
01:35:59,086 --> 01:36:00,962
[BOTH SPEAK IN SPANISH]

1526
01:36:01,130 --> 01:36:03,757
This must be a bit
of a shock, I guess.

1527
01:36:04,341 --> 01:36:06,676
ANNOUNCER 1: Mabry hits one
deep to right-center field.

1528
01:36:06,844 --> 01:36:08,845
Racing back, Fick can't get it.

1529
01:36:09,013 --> 01:36:12,640
It bounces to the wall.
One run is in. Two runs are in.

1530
01:36:13,058 --> 01:36:16,352
Mabry, on one pitch,
has shot the A's in front.

1531
01:36:16,520 --> 01:36:20,857
Strike three called.
Twelve straight wins
for the Athletics.

1532
01:36:21,025 --> 01:36:22,442
Man alive, was it hairy.

1533
01:36:22,610 --> 01:36:25,028
ANNOUNCER 2:
Something strange is now
happening in Oakland.

1534
01:36:25,196 --> 01:36:27,614
You cannot argue that point.
ANNOUNCER 1: Twelve straight.

1535
01:36:27,782 --> 01:36:30,700
ANNOUNCER 3:
They're making a joke
out of the American League.

1536
01:36:30,868 --> 01:36:33,453
They were in Detroit today--
ANNOUNCER 1: He throws to first.

1537
01:36:33,621 --> 01:36:37,165
And that's the sound
of 14 straight victories.

1538
01:36:37,333 --> 01:36:39,375
Fourteen, the longest run
this year.

1539
01:36:39,543 --> 01:36:42,629
It has slingshot the A's into first
in the AL West. A nice streak.

1540
01:36:42,797 --> 01:36:44,631
ANNOUNCER 4:
This team was written off.

1541
01:36:44,799 --> 01:36:48,259
How do you explain, otherwise,
the victories they've come up with?

1542
01:36:48,427 --> 01:36:51,971
ANNOUNCER 5:
The Oakland A's are gonna win
16 consecutive games.

1543
01:36:53,015 --> 01:36:59,062
This is the longest win streak
in baseball, folks, in 25 years.

1544
01:36:59,230 --> 01:37:01,064
The A's have won 16 in a row.

1545
01:37:01,232 --> 01:37:03,817
CALLER 1:
We're going to 20!
We're going to 20!

1546
01:37:03,984 --> 01:37:08,238
ANNOUNCER 6:
To have a winning streak of
this duration, you have to be good,

1547
01:37:08,405 --> 01:37:11,324
but there's an element
of randomness to it.

1548
01:37:11,492 --> 01:37:13,701
The 1927 Yankees, Ruth, Gehrig,

1549
01:37:13,869 --> 01:37:16,996
Murderers' Row, some people
still say the best team ever.

1550
01:37:17,164 --> 01:37:20,708
Longest winning streak
for them that year? Nine.

1551
01:37:20,876 --> 01:37:23,878
CALLER 2:
You guys try to analyze it
from a numbers standpoint.

1552
01:37:24,046 --> 01:37:28,091
I'm telling you, there is
no explanation for what's
occurring right now.

1553
01:37:28,259 --> 01:37:30,134
INTERVIEWER:
Do you have superstitions going on?

1554
01:37:30,302 --> 01:37:32,637
Do you do things
so you keep the streak alive?

1555
01:37:32,805 --> 01:37:36,349
ANNOUNCER 7:
The all-time record of 20
does not seem impossible anymore.

1556
01:37:36,517 --> 01:37:38,852
ANNOUNCER 8:
The A's were on page one
ofthe New York Times.

1557
01:37:39,019 --> 01:37:42,397
They are the story in sports
in this entire country.

1558
01:37:42,565 --> 01:37:43,940
ANNOUNCER 9:
Two-two pitch, here it is.

1559
01:37:44,108 --> 01:37:48,194
Swing and a miss! Struck him out!
Number 17!

1560
01:37:48,362 --> 01:37:51,281
It's taken 71 years.

1561
01:37:51,448 --> 01:37:54,367
The Oakland A's
have tied the Philadelphia A's.

1562
01:37:54,535 --> 01:37:58,454
The all-time franchise record
17 straight

1563
01:37:58,622 --> 01:38:03,877
and baseball's longest
winning streak since 1953.

1564
01:38:04,044 --> 01:38:07,964
ANNOUNCER 10:
The A's are two wins away from
tying the American League record.

1565
01:38:08,132 --> 01:38:13,803
ANNOUNCER 5:
It's gone! It's gone! Tejada wins it!
Do you believe it?

1566
01:38:14,305 --> 01:38:16,472
Eighteen wins in a row!

1567
01:38:16,640 --> 01:38:19,559
ANNOUNCER 6:
You could replay these 18 games
a hundred times over.

1568
01:38:19,727 --> 01:38:21,644
And nobody wins
18 straight again.

1569
01:38:21,812 --> 01:38:24,355
It defies everything we know
about baseball.

1570
01:38:24,815 --> 01:38:28,151
ANNOUNCER 10:
The most amazing thing
you could imagine

1571
01:38:28,319 --> 01:38:31,279
happened over the last four days
at the Coliseum.

1572
01:38:31,447 --> 01:38:36,993
ANNOUNCER 5:
Tejada, up the middle.
The A's have won 19 in a row!

1573
01:38:37,912 --> 01:38:40,496
ANNOUNCER 10:
The 1906 White Sox,

1574
01:38:40,664 --> 01:38:44,667
the 1947 New York Yankees
have company.

1575
01:38:45,920 --> 01:38:47,420
Nineteen in a row.

1576
01:38:47,588 --> 01:38:50,506
ANNOUNCER 11:
The A's have a date with destiny.

1577
01:38:50,674 --> 01:38:53,718
They're going for the all-time
American League record,

1578
01:38:53,886 --> 01:38:55,011
20 games in a row.

1579
01:38:55,179 --> 01:38:59,474
CALLER 1: We're going to 20!
We're gonna take the AL record
to 20, baby!

1580
01:39:00,851 --> 01:39:02,185
[CELL PHONE RINGS]

1581
01:39:02,353 --> 01:39:04,187
BILLY:
Don't tell me the score, Pete.

1582
01:39:04,355 --> 01:39:05,730
SHARON [OVER SPEAKER]:
No, Billy, it's me.

1583
01:39:05,898 --> 01:39:08,149
Sharon?
Yeah.

1584
01:39:09,360 --> 01:39:12,528
You have a second?
Yeah, what's up?

1585
01:39:12,696 --> 01:39:15,073
Well, I didn't actually
expect you to pick up.

1586
01:39:15,240 --> 01:39:17,033
I was gonna leave a message.

1587
01:39:17,201 --> 01:39:21,037
Um, Casey and I, we're here
and watching the game at home.

1588
01:39:21,205 --> 01:39:24,874
And I just wanted to say...

1589
01:39:26,210 --> 01:39:27,961
you did good, Billy.

1590
01:39:28,128 --> 01:39:30,171
We're really proud of you.

1591
01:39:31,674 --> 01:39:34,008
I appreciate it, Sharon.

1592
01:39:34,176 --> 01:39:37,053
Thank you.
Good luck.

1593
01:39:37,846 --> 01:39:38,888
Okay.

1594
01:39:39,056 --> 01:39:41,391
Oh, Casey wants to talk to you.
Hang on.

1595
01:39:42,184 --> 01:39:43,977
CASEY:
Are you on your way
to the stadium?

1596
01:39:44,144 --> 01:39:47,188
No, I'm on my way to Visalia
to see our minor-league team.

1597
01:39:47,356 --> 01:39:50,108
Turn around, please, Dad.
No way, Jose.

1598
01:39:50,275 --> 01:39:52,986
Turn around. Come on, Dad.
Nope. Not gonna happen.

1599
01:39:53,153 --> 01:39:54,487
You're not gonna jinx it.

1600
01:39:54,655 --> 01:39:58,241
I'll talk to you later, sweetheart.
I love you.

1601
01:39:58,575 --> 01:39:59,867
[CELL PHONE BEEPS]

1602
01:40:04,748 --> 01:40:06,124
Shit.

1603
01:40:06,291 --> 01:40:09,419
ANNOUNCER 1 [ON RADIO]:
One out here in the fourth,
and if you're just joining us,

1604
01:40:09,586 --> 01:40:10,670
you missed a lot.

1605
01:40:10,838 --> 01:40:13,881
And the pitch to Raul Ibanez.
Strike one.

1606
01:40:14,049 --> 01:40:15,758
ANNOUNCER 2:
I think my recap will be simple.

1607
01:40:15,926 --> 01:40:19,595
The A's scored six in the first,
one in the second, four in the third.

1608
01:40:19,763 --> 01:40:23,349
ANNOUNCER 1:
And people would be shocked
if you just did that. Heh-heh-heh.

1609
01:40:23,517 --> 01:40:25,768
Eleven to nothing, the A's do lead.

1610
01:40:25,936 --> 01:40:28,646
Shit.
Foul off the foot of Ibanez...

1611
01:40:30,441 --> 01:40:32,442
[♪♪♪]

1612
01:40:51,128 --> 01:40:53,755
CROWD [CHANTING]:
Let's go, Oakland!

1613
01:40:53,922 --> 01:40:59,260
Let's go, Oakland!

1614
01:40:59,428 --> 01:41:01,763
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

1615
01:41:04,683 --> 01:41:10,813
ANNOUNCER 1 [OVER PA]:
Now batting, number 2,
catcher, Brent Mayne.

1616
01:41:14,943 --> 01:41:18,905
MAN 1: Oakland!
MAN 2: Here we go, Oakland!

1617
01:41:27,498 --> 01:41:29,082
PLAYER:
Two.

1618
01:41:30,709 --> 01:41:32,376
UMPIRE:
Safe.

1619
01:41:37,758 --> 01:41:39,217
ANNOUNCER 1 [OVER PA]:
Now batting,

1620
01:41:39,384 --> 01:41:45,014
number 18,
left fielder Raul Ibanez.

1621
01:41:46,683 --> 01:41:48,684
[♪♪♪]

1622
01:42:31,395 --> 01:42:32,728
[BAT CRACKS]

1623
01:42:35,232 --> 01:42:37,400
[SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

1624
01:42:46,201 --> 01:42:47,785
Safe.

1625
01:42:50,205 --> 01:42:52,582
ANNOUNCER 2 [ON TV]:
And the A's now lead
by a score of 11 to 3.

1626
01:42:52,749 --> 01:42:55,585
ANNOUNCER 3: A nice cushion,
but you don't wanna give teams life

1627
01:42:55,752 --> 01:42:58,421
and let them wedge their way
back in, even when you're--

1628
01:42:58,589 --> 01:43:00,590
[BAT CRACKS]

1629
01:43:16,648 --> 01:43:18,649
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

1630
01:43:29,369 --> 01:43:30,870
[BAT CRACKS]

1631
01:43:42,424 --> 01:43:44,133
ANNOUNCER 3:
Nobody out, the bases loaded.

1632
01:43:44,301 --> 01:43:47,637
And Art Howe on the way to the
mound to make a pitching change.

1633
01:43:47,804 --> 01:43:49,722
And this game is still in a state

1634
01:43:49,890 --> 01:43:52,808
where it could get out of control
for the Athletics.

1635
01:43:59,483 --> 01:44:02,735
JONGEWAARD:
We're all told at some point we can
no longer play the children's game.

1636
01:44:02,903 --> 01:44:06,489
We just don't know
when that's gonna be.

1637
01:44:10,077 --> 01:44:15,539
Some of us are told at 18,
some of us are told at 40,
but we're all told.

1638
01:44:15,707 --> 01:44:18,042
ANNOUNCER 3:
Mike Sweeney with runners
at first and third.

1639
01:44:18,210 --> 01:44:20,628
It's an 11-to-7 game,
the A's in front.

1640
01:44:20,796 --> 01:44:23,506
Tam peering in for the sign.

1641
01:44:23,674 --> 01:44:26,676
Two out. Runners at first and third.

1642
01:44:26,843 --> 01:44:29,303
And the 3-2 delivery.

1643
01:44:50,575 --> 01:44:52,952
[♪♪♪]

1644
01:45:03,046 --> 01:45:05,381
MAN:
It's weird, Billy.

1645
01:45:05,549 --> 01:45:09,593
You wanna give up baseball
to become a scout?

1646
01:45:10,929 --> 01:45:13,347
BILLY:
I'm not a baseball player.

1647
01:45:13,765 --> 01:45:16,225
MAN:
Are you sure this is what you want?

1648
01:45:17,561 --> 01:45:22,148
ANNOUNCER 3:
The crowd is roaring.
Koch is ready. One-two pitch.

1649
01:45:22,607 --> 01:45:25,901
Alicea puts it in play,
a looper to left field for a base hit.

1650
01:45:26,069 --> 01:45:29,488
Around third, tearing for the plate,
here comes the tying run.

1651
01:45:29,698 --> 01:45:33,701
Sliding safe.
And the ball game is tied at 11-all.

1652
01:45:33,869 --> 01:45:35,494
Holy Toledo.

1653
01:45:36,788 --> 01:45:41,083
The A's have blown
an 11 -to-nothing lead.

1654
01:45:42,836 --> 01:45:46,922
This is the specter of a development
that has been lurking now

1655
01:45:47,382 --> 01:45:51,510
ever since the five-run fourth inning
by the Royals.

1656
01:45:51,678 --> 01:45:57,099
And the A's date with destiny
is on hold right now.

1657
01:46:00,103 --> 01:46:02,104
[CROWD CHEERING]

1658
01:46:22,709 --> 01:46:25,961
ART:
Hatteberg. Hattie.

1659
01:46:26,463 --> 01:46:28,964
Grab a bat.
You're hitting for Byrnesy.

1660
01:46:30,467 --> 01:46:33,803
Come on, let's go.
Get yourself loose.

1661
01:46:44,147 --> 01:46:48,025
ANNOUNCER 1 [OVER PA]:
Hitting for Eric Byrnes,

1662
01:46:48,193 --> 01:46:52,363
number 10, Scott Hatteberg.

1663
01:46:53,615 --> 01:46:55,616
[♪♪♪]

1664
01:47:00,497 --> 01:47:04,125
ANNOUNCER 3:
In your typical A's fashion.
They want a base runner here.

1665
01:47:04,292 --> 01:47:08,003
Scott Hatteberg is so adept
at drawing walks.

1666
01:47:11,216 --> 01:47:13,509
He's looking for Hatteberg
to get on base,

1667
01:47:13,677 --> 01:47:15,678
maybe bring in a pinch runner.

1668
01:47:15,846 --> 01:47:18,264
CROWD [CHANTING]:
Let's go, Oakland!

1669
01:47:18,432 --> 01:47:20,516
Let's go, Oakland!

1670
01:47:59,890 --> 01:48:01,015
[BAT CRACKS]

1671
01:48:12,235 --> 01:48:14,236
[♪♪♪]

1672
01:48:15,322 --> 01:48:17,114
ANNOUNCER 3:
That one is gone!

1673
01:48:17,282 --> 01:48:21,744
And it's 20 consecutive victories
for the Oakland Athletics

1674
01:48:21,912 --> 01:48:23,954
on an unbelievable night

1675
01:48:24,122 --> 01:48:26,790
when they lost
an 11 -to-nothing lead

1676
01:48:26,958 --> 01:48:28,459
and now they win it.

1677
01:48:28,627 --> 01:48:30,503
[CHEERING]

1678
01:48:30,670 --> 01:48:35,174
The crowd comes back
to insane life.

1679
01:48:37,093 --> 01:48:39,094
How do you explain it?

1680
01:48:40,055 --> 01:48:44,391
Crazy. Just plain crazy.

1681
01:48:48,480 --> 01:48:52,066
Hatteberg is mobbed
at home plate.

1682
01:48:55,278 --> 01:48:58,280
In 103 years
of American League baseball,

1683
01:48:58,448 --> 01:49:01,909
the Athletics have accomplished
what no one has before.

1684
01:49:02,077 --> 01:49:06,288
They have won
20 consecutive games.

1685
01:49:32,315 --> 01:49:35,109
BILLY:
It's hard not to be romantic
about baseball.

1686
01:49:36,987 --> 01:49:40,239
This kind of thing,
it's fun for the fans.

1687
01:49:41,157 --> 01:49:44,577
It sells tickets and hot dogs.

1688
01:49:45,870 --> 01:49:47,496
Doesn't mean anything.

1689
01:49:47,664 --> 01:49:51,292
PETER:
Billy, we just won
20 games in a row.

1690
01:49:53,003 --> 01:49:55,045
And what's the point?

1691
01:49:55,213 --> 01:49:57,881
PETER:
We just got the record.

1692
01:50:00,802 --> 01:50:03,178
Man, I've been doing this for...

1693
01:50:09,185 --> 01:50:11,270
Listen, man.

1694
01:50:11,438 --> 01:50:14,898
I've been in this game
a long time.

1695
01:50:16,526 --> 01:50:19,278
I'm not in it for a record,
I'll tell you that.

1696
01:50:19,446 --> 01:50:21,572
I'm not in it for a ring.

1697
01:50:24,242 --> 01:50:26,493
That's when
people get hurt.

1698
01:50:28,121 --> 01:50:31,040
If we don't win the last game
of the Series,

1699
01:50:32,292 --> 01:50:34,335
they'll dismiss us.

1700
01:50:34,878 --> 01:50:36,337
Billy--
I know these guys.

1701
01:50:36,504 --> 01:50:39,381
I know the way they think,
and they will erase us.

1702
01:50:40,884 --> 01:50:43,385
And everything
we've done here,

1703
01:50:43,553 --> 01:50:45,471
none of it'll matter.

1704
01:50:48,558 --> 01:50:51,894
Any other team wins
the World Series, good for them.

1705
01:50:53,063 --> 01:50:56,398
They're drinking champagne,
they get a ring.

1706
01:50:56,566 --> 01:50:58,525
But if we win,

1707
01:50:59,110 --> 01:51:01,779
on our budget, with this team...

1708
01:51:05,575 --> 01:51:07,618
we'll have changed the game.

1709
01:51:08,411 --> 01:51:10,579
And that's what I want.

1710
01:51:10,747 --> 01:51:12,998
I want it to mean something.

1711
01:51:21,257 --> 01:51:22,466
[♪♪♪]

1712
01:51:22,634 --> 01:51:26,762
ANNOUNCER 1:
The A's going to the play-offs
with the West Division title.

1713
01:51:26,930 --> 01:51:29,682
ANNOUNCER 2:
Forgive the A's
if they're not celebrating.

1714
01:51:29,849 --> 01:51:31,392
They have been here before,

1715
01:51:31,559 --> 01:51:35,270
when Oakland went up two games
to none on the Yanks in the ALDS,

1716
01:51:35,438 --> 01:51:37,940
and went nowhere
after losing three straight.

1717
01:51:38,108 --> 01:51:41,443
With a win today over the Twins,
Oakland moves into the ALCS

1718
01:51:41,611 --> 01:51:44,279
for the first time since 1992.

1719
01:51:44,447 --> 01:51:46,156
ANNOUNCER 3:
But remember one thing.

1720
01:51:46,324 --> 01:51:50,160
Percentages hold up over a season,
but for one game, one at bat,

1721
01:51:50,328 --> 01:51:52,871
throw the percentages
out the window.

1722
01:51:53,039 --> 01:51:55,040
[CROWD CHEERING]

1723
01:52:25,655 --> 01:52:30,200
ANNOUNCER 4:
What the Minnesota Twins exposed
is the fact that the Oakland A's

1724
01:52:30,368 --> 01:52:34,163
were fundamentally
not a sound baseball team.

1725
01:52:34,330 --> 01:52:37,833
They had a flawed concept that
started with the general manager

1726
01:52:38,001 --> 01:52:41,503
and the brain trust thinking
they could reinvent baseball.

1727
01:52:41,671 --> 01:52:43,255
You can't approach baseball

1728
01:52:43,423 --> 01:52:46,091
from a statistical,
bean-counting point of view.

1729
01:52:46,259 --> 01:52:48,510
It's won on the field
with fundamental play.

1730
01:52:48,678 --> 01:52:51,764
You have to steal, you have to bunt,
you have to sacrifice.

1731
01:52:51,931 --> 01:52:55,517
You gotta get men
in scoring position,
and you gotta bring them in.

1732
01:52:55,685 --> 01:53:00,147
And you don't do that
with a bunch of statistical gimmicks.

1733
01:53:00,315 --> 01:53:03,150
Nobody reinvents this game.

1734
01:53:07,781 --> 01:53:09,782
[♪♪♪]

1735
01:53:15,413 --> 01:53:17,414
[BOTTLE CAP CLATTERS]

1736
01:53:17,957 --> 01:53:19,208
[LIQUID POURING]

1737
01:53:39,562 --> 01:53:41,230
[CELL PHONE RINGING]

1738
01:53:46,361 --> 01:53:47,778
Yeah.

1739
01:53:53,910 --> 01:53:55,911
[♪♪♪]

1740
01:54:56,306 --> 01:55:01,810
HENRY:
Due respect to the Coliseum,
but this is a ballpark.

1741
01:55:01,978 --> 01:55:03,979
BILLY:
Yes, it is.

1742
01:55:06,065 --> 01:55:08,317
We're gonna have
some lunch in a little bit.

1743
01:55:08,484 --> 01:55:10,736
Why don't I have
some coffee sent up?

1744
01:55:11,404 --> 01:55:13,155
Denise?

1745
01:55:17,785 --> 01:55:19,661
HENRY:
Thank you, Denise.

1746
01:55:19,829 --> 01:55:21,872
BILLY: Thanks.
You're welcome.

1747
01:55:24,834 --> 01:55:28,503
You know, it's her birthday
and I need to get her a present,

1748
01:55:28,671 --> 01:55:31,632
but she's usually the one
that does that for me.

1749
01:55:32,342 --> 01:55:34,676
So do you
have any ideas?

1750
01:55:35,219 --> 01:55:36,595
Scarf.

1751
01:55:36,763 --> 01:55:38,221
You mean like wool?

1752
01:55:38,389 --> 01:55:43,352
No, I meant what women wear with...
You know, decorative.

1753
01:55:43,519 --> 01:55:46,521
Ah. And where would
I get something like that?

1754
01:55:47,482 --> 01:55:50,817
No disrespect, I just lost in five
for the second year in a row.

1755
01:55:50,985 --> 01:55:53,320
Get her a bowling ball
for all I care.

1756
01:55:53,488 --> 01:55:54,863
Right.

1757
01:55:55,782 --> 01:55:59,326
Well, Steve told me
he's offering you a new contract.

1758
01:56:00,787 --> 01:56:02,496
Yes.

1759
01:56:02,664 --> 01:56:05,332
So why did you return my call?

1760
01:56:07,418 --> 01:56:10,003
Because it's the Red Sox.

1761
01:56:10,171 --> 01:56:14,716
Because I believe science
might offer an answer to
the Curse of the Bambino.

1762
01:56:15,385 --> 01:56:20,681
Because I hear you hired Bill James.
Yup.

1763
01:56:20,848 --> 01:56:25,560
You know, why someone took so long
to hire that guy is beyond me.

1764
01:56:26,521 --> 01:56:28,855
Well, baseball hates him.

1765
01:56:29,399 --> 01:56:34,111
Well, baseball can hate him,
you know.

1766
01:56:34,278 --> 01:56:38,240
One of the great things about money
is that it buys a lot of things,

1767
01:56:38,408 --> 01:56:41,952
one of which is the luxury
to disregard what baseball likes,

1768
01:56:42,120 --> 01:56:45,080
doesn't like, what baseball thinks,
doesn't think.

1769
01:56:45,248 --> 01:56:46,540
[CHUCKLES]

1770
01:56:46,708 --> 01:56:49,334
Ah. Sounds nice.

1771
01:56:50,044 --> 01:56:51,420
Well...

1772
01:56:52,088 --> 01:56:54,131
I was grateful for the call.

1773
01:56:54,298 --> 01:56:56,174
You were grateful?
Yeah.

1774
01:56:59,429 --> 01:57:03,306
For 41 million,
you built a play-off team.

1775
01:57:03,474 --> 01:57:07,769
You lost Damon, Giambi,
Isringhausen, Pena,

1776
01:57:08,229 --> 01:57:11,606
and you won more games
without them than you did
with them.

1777
01:57:11,774 --> 01:57:15,193
You won the exact same number
of games that the Yankees won,

1778
01:57:15,361 --> 01:57:19,281
but the Yankees spent
1 .4 million per win,

1779
01:57:19,449 --> 01:57:22,909
and you paid 260,000.

1780
01:57:23,077 --> 01:57:27,122
I know you're taking it in the teeth,
but the first guy through the wall,

1781
01:57:27,582 --> 01:57:29,750
he always gets bloody.

1782
01:57:29,917 --> 01:57:33,295
Always. This is threatening
not just a way of doing business,

1783
01:57:33,463 --> 01:57:36,006
but in their minds,
it's threatening the game.

1784
01:57:36,174 --> 01:57:39,468
Really, what it's threatening
is their livelihood, their jobs.

1785
01:57:39,635 --> 01:57:42,637
It's threatening the way
that they do things.

1786
01:57:42,805 --> 01:57:44,181
Every time that happens,

1787
01:57:44,348 --> 01:57:47,851
whether it's a government,
a way of doing business, whatever,

1788
01:57:48,019 --> 01:57:50,562
the people
who are holding the reins,

1789
01:57:50,730 --> 01:57:53,315
they have their hands
on the switch,

1790
01:57:53,483 --> 01:57:55,984
they go batshit crazy.

1791
01:57:56,986 --> 01:58:01,823
I mean, anybody who's not
tearing their team down right now

1792
01:58:01,991 --> 01:58:05,118
and rebuilding it
using your model,

1793
01:58:05,995 --> 01:58:07,829
they're dinosaurs.

1794
01:58:08,414 --> 01:58:12,834
They'll be sitting on their ass
on the sofa in October

1795
01:58:13,002 --> 01:58:16,505
watching the Boston Red Sox
win the World Series.

1796
01:58:21,886 --> 01:58:23,804
What's this?

1797
01:58:23,971 --> 01:58:27,474
I want you to be
my general manager.
That's my offer.

1798
01:58:41,364 --> 01:58:43,365
[♪♪♪]

1799
01:59:14,397 --> 01:59:15,897
PETER:
Heads up.

1800
01:59:17,567 --> 01:59:18,567
What was that?

1801
01:59:19,819 --> 01:59:22,904
Sorry. I don't know.
What the hell was that?

1802
01:59:23,573 --> 01:59:25,907
You knucklehead.

1803
01:59:33,416 --> 01:59:34,749
How was Boston?

1804
01:59:36,294 --> 01:59:38,211
Impressive.

1805
01:59:44,635 --> 01:59:47,262
Did Henry make you
a good offer, at least?

1806
01:59:48,806 --> 01:59:51,892
Doesn't matter. Doesn't matter.
What was it? What was it?

1807
01:59:52,059 --> 01:59:53,685
Doesn't matter.
What was it?

1808
02:00:16,751 --> 02:00:20,253
That makes you
the highest-paid GM
in the history of sports.

1809
02:00:22,673 --> 02:00:24,132
So?

1810
02:00:25,968 --> 02:00:27,177
So what?

1811
02:00:30,223 --> 02:00:32,682
I made one decision in my life
based on money.

1812
02:00:32,850 --> 02:00:35,810
And I swore
I would never do it again.

1813
02:00:38,397 --> 02:00:40,440
You're not doing it
for the money.

1814
02:00:40,942 --> 02:00:43,443
No?
No.

1815
02:00:45,446 --> 02:00:47,989
You're doing it
for what the money says.

1816
02:00:49,408 --> 02:00:53,119
And it says what it says to any
player that makes big money.

1817
02:00:53,788 --> 02:00:55,538
That they're worth it.

1818
02:01:04,006 --> 02:01:05,715
What a dump.

1819
02:01:09,887 --> 02:01:12,222
I really wanted to win here.

1820
02:01:16,269 --> 02:01:18,812
I really did.

1821
02:01:21,315 --> 02:01:23,483
I think you won pretty big, Billy.

1822
02:01:24,318 --> 02:01:26,444
Pete, we lost.

1823
02:01:28,030 --> 02:01:30,615
We lost.

1824
02:01:30,783 --> 02:01:34,244
It's only been a few days.
Give yourself some time
to get over it.

1825
02:01:34,412 --> 02:01:37,747
Man, I don't
get over these things.

1826
02:01:37,915 --> 02:01:39,040
Ever.

1827
02:01:46,048 --> 02:01:49,718
Come with me to the video room.
I wanna show you something.

1828
02:01:51,470 --> 02:01:54,764
No, man,
I'm not up for film right now.

1829
02:01:56,017 --> 02:01:58,101
Come on. Seriously.

1830
02:01:58,269 --> 02:02:00,437
Come on, Billy.
Come on.

1831
02:02:02,148 --> 02:02:03,273
PETER:
The Visalia Oaks

1832
02:02:03,441 --> 02:02:06,234
and our 240-pound catcher,
Jeremy Brown,

1833
02:02:06,402 --> 02:02:10,030
who, as you know,
is scared to run to second base.

1834
02:02:10,197 --> 02:02:11,990
This was in a game six weeks ago.

1835
02:02:12,575 --> 02:02:14,701
This guy's gonna start
with a fastball.

1836
02:02:14,869 --> 02:02:17,287
Jeremy's gonna take him
to deep center.

1837
02:02:19,457 --> 02:02:20,957
Here's what's interesting,

1838
02:02:21,125 --> 02:02:24,002
because Jeremy's gonna do
what he never does.

1839
02:02:24,170 --> 02:02:25,462
He's gonna go for it.

1840
02:02:25,629 --> 02:02:28,882
He's gonna round first
and he's gonna go for it.

1841
02:02:30,092 --> 02:02:31,384
Okay?

1842
02:02:34,680 --> 02:02:39,642
This is all of Jeremy's
nightmares coming to life.

1843
02:02:42,104 --> 02:02:45,523
Aw, they're laughing at him.
And Jeremy's about to find out why.

1844
02:02:48,694 --> 02:02:51,071
Jeremy's about to realize

1845
02:02:52,531 --> 02:02:55,658
that the ball went 60 feet
over the fence.

1846
02:02:58,287 --> 02:03:01,915
He hit a home run
and didn't even realize it.

1847
02:03:31,904 --> 02:03:34,948
How can you not be romantic
about baseball?

1848
02:03:39,870 --> 02:03:42,789
It's a metaphor.
I know it's a metaphor.

1849
02:03:47,503 --> 02:03:48,878
Okay.

1850
02:03:52,967 --> 02:03:56,010
Pete, you're a good egg.

1851
02:03:59,432 --> 02:04:01,182
I'll call you.

1852
02:04:02,977 --> 02:04:04,978
[♪♪♪]

1853
02:05:01,994 --> 02:05:05,580
CASEY [ON RECORDING]:
Hey, Dad, this is the song
I told you I'd record.

1854
02:05:05,748 --> 02:05:08,458
Please don't show it
to anyone else.

1855
02:05:08,626 --> 02:05:11,711
Let me know if you change
your mind and stay in California.

1856
02:05:11,879 --> 02:05:14,923
If not, you're a really great dad.

1857
02:05:20,262 --> 02:05:23,223
♪ I'm just a little bit
Caught in the middle ♪

1858
02:05:23,390 --> 02:05:26,601
♪ Life is a maze
And love is a riddle ♪

1859
02:05:26,769 --> 02:05:31,564
♪ I don't know where to go
Can't do it alone, I've tried ♪

1860
02:05:31,732 --> 02:05:33,441
♪ And I don't know why ♪

1861
02:05:33,609 --> 02:05:36,277
♪ I'm just a little girl
Lost in the moment ♪

1862
02:05:36,445 --> 02:05:39,364
♪ I'm so scared
But I don't show it ♪

1863
02:05:39,532 --> 02:05:43,117
♪ I can't figure it out
It's bringing me down ♪

1864
02:05:43,285 --> 02:05:48,039
♪ I know I've got to let it go ♪

1865
02:05:48,207 --> 02:05:50,458
♪ And just enjoy the show ♪

1866
02:05:50,626 --> 02:05:53,503
♪ Slow it down, make it stop ♪

1867
02:05:53,671 --> 02:05:57,090
♪ Or else my heart
Is going to pop ♪

1868
02:05:57,258 --> 02:06:00,885
♪ 'Cause it's too much
Yeah, it's a lot ♪

1869
02:06:01,762 --> 02:06:04,347
♪ To be something I'm not ♪

1870
02:06:04,515 --> 02:06:08,101
♪ I'm a fool, out of love ♪

1871
02:06:08,269 --> 02:06:13,648
♪ And I just can't get enough ♪

1872
02:06:13,816 --> 02:06:16,818
♪ I'm just a little bit
Caught in the middle ♪

